<HEADLINE> Albania Ready to Serve NATO's Logistics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Albania is ready to offer logistics
services with flight and landing facilities for NATO's display of
strength against Yugoslavia over the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Albania is ready to put its logistics at the disposal of NATO
and offers flight and landing facilities to its warplanes, as it
happened today," Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano said Monday in
talks with Swedish Defense Minister Bjorn Fon Sydov, who arrived
for a one-day visit to Tirana.
</P>
<P>
NATO warplanes began air exercises over the southern Balkans on
Monday, designed to show that western diplomacy aimed at stopping
bloodshed in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo is backed by
military force.
</P>
<P>
The wargames came as fighting continued in Kosovo over the
weekend and Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic prepared to
hold talks in Moscow with Russian President Boris Yeltsin aimed at
averting military intervention in the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Nano also hoped the bloc would reinforce its military presence
in Albania, which borders Kosovo where ethnic Albanians clashed
with Serbian authorities over independence from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's support for Albania's integration into the 15-state
European Union would help reduce tensions in the region, said
Nano, referring to the conflict which the international community
fears could spread through the southern Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish Defense Minister said NATO and other international
organizations would continue to follow the situation closely and
respect the deadlines given to Belgrade to withdraw troops from
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
