<HEADLINE> Canada's Teleglobe Merges with U.S. Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada's telecommunications giant
Teleglobe Inc. is to merge with Excel Communications Inc. to
create the fourth-largest long-distance phone company in North
America with a market valuation of seven billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued late Sunday, the two companies said
the merger will combine Teleglobe's extensive intercontinental
network and Excel's strong U.S. network.
</P>
<P>
The Montreal-based company and its U.S. partner hope to be
better positioned to tap an estimated 150 billion dollar market
among the group of the seven industrialized countries (G7) where
Teleglobe is licensed to operate.
</P>
<P>
The new Teleglobe Inc. company will be based in Montreal. It
will serve 275 carriers world-wide, employ 4,800 people and carry
long-distance traffic for six million residential and about 65,000
business customers.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to have a revenue of about 3.5 billion dollars
annually, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Excel ranks as the fifth-largest long-distance phone company in
the United States, after AT&AMP;T, MCI, Sprint and Worldcom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
