<HEADLINE> EU Fiance Ministers Urge Japan to Carry out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARDIFF, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) finance
ministers Monday urged Japan to carry out further reforms in an
effort to restore consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
During the on-going EU summit which was opened early Monday in
Welsh capital of Cardiff, finance ministers from all the 15-nation
bloc said in a written statement that they discussed the latest
economic situation in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"We noted the data published in Japan on Friday which showed
GDP falling by 1.3 percent in the first quarter of this year. The
economic impact of the recently announced fiscal stimulus has
still to come through," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The EU ministers stressed that it was necessary for Japan to
implement "further necessary structural reforms and measures to
strengthen the financial system to restore business and consumer
confidence.
</P>
<P>
On the latest developments in Indonesia, the ministers welcomed
Indonesia's statements committing itself to economic and political
reform and stressed the importance of both transparency and its
continuing "good cooperation" with international financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
"We recognized the economic hardship faced by the people of
Indonesia and welcomed the humanitarian assistance being provided
by the European Community and member states individually," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The European ministers also voiced support for the Russian
government's economic reforms, in particular the reforms to
strengthen the tax administration and improve tax collection.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to consider further conditional support for
Russia as necessary and appropriate," the statement said, adding
"any such assistance should be provided by the IMF (International
Monetary Fund) and the World Bank."  
</P>
</TEXT>
