<HEADLINE> Zambia to Probe Alleged Torture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is working
out modalities for the establishment of an independent inquiry to
probe alleged torture of the detainees involved in the October 28
failed coup, Home Affairs Minister Peter Machungwa said Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said here that the government has not abandoned the idea of
setting up the independent inquiry commission at an appropriate
time.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation to set up an independent commission of
inquiry into allegations of torture of the coup suspects by
police was made by the permanent human rights commission of the
country early this year.
</P>
<P>
Legal Affairs Minister Vincent Malambo also assured the donors
attending the Paris Club consultative meeting in May that an
independent inquiry would be conducted.
</P>
<P>
The police service was identified as the root cause of human
rights abuses and as such a vigorous restructuring and retaining
program will be devised for presentation at the next donors
meeting late this year.
</P>
<P>
At the Paris meeting the donors pledged Zambia 530 million
U.S. Dollars and additional funding once some governance and
human rights issues are resolved.
</P>
<P>
In another development, trial of 79 treason suspects of the
coup was adjourned for the second time Monday because one of the
soldiers is still recovering in hospital from an operation.
</P>
<P>
High Court Judge Japhet Banda adjourned the case to next
Monday, an application made by leader of the defense group for an
adjournment to allow Frazer Jere to recover from a surgical
operation carried out last Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
