<HEADLINE> Canada's Nortel Buys Bay Networks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada's telecommunications giant
Northern Telecom Ltd. (Nortel) announced Monday that it is buying
California-based Bay Networks for 9.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of agreement, Bay Networks shareholders will
receive a fixed exchange ratio of 0.60 of a Nortel common share
for each share of their stocks.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Nortel expects to issue about 134 million common
shares to close the purchase.
</P>
<P>
This represents a price of 38.21 per share of Bay Networks and
9.1 billion U.S. dollars for the entire transaction, according to
a statement issued by Nortel.
</P>
<P>
Bay Networks shareholders will own 21 percent of Nortel when
the deal is completed in the third quarter. And Bay Networks will
operate as a wholly owned subsidiary of Nortel.
</P>
<P>
Nortel said it is one of the world's largest suppliers of
digital network solution, while Bay Networks is a leader in the
worldwide data networking market.
</P>
<P>
"This transaction creates a new category of company suited to
this era -- an era of end-to-end, mission-critical IP networks,"
said John Roth, president and chief executive officer of Nortel.
</P>
<P>
"Our combined business will be ideally constructed to meet this
need, in terms of complementary expertise, products and
distribution," Roth said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
