<HEADLINE> England Won't Be Kicked Out, FIFA Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Despite the troubles England hooligans
caused at Marseille, FIFA official insisted that there was no danger
of England being kicked out of the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
England hooligans clashed with Tunisian supporters and French
police before and during the Group G match between England and
Tunisia at Marseille. The clashes left 37 people in hospital and
more than 30 English fans were arrested.
</P>
<P>
But FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper said:"The England football team
are not responsible for a handful of people throwing chairs through
cafe windows. There's no reason to remove the team from the
competition. It's not even a point of discussion."
</P>
<P>
Cooper also insisted that the hooliganism would not affect
England's chances of staging the 2006 World Cup finals:"I don't
think we should confuse these two things. They're two completely
separate issues." Cooper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
