<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Energy Ministers Convene in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The energy ministers of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) Monday began their
23rd meeting in Harare on regional power policies.
</P>
<P>
The week-long meeting, being attended by ministers responsible
for energy from 14 SADC member countries, would map out how
investment can be maximized in this sector to boost economic
development.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Zimbabwe's Transport and Energy
Minister Enos Chikowore called on governments in the region to
come up with innovative financing infrastructures to ensure their
power utilities and the new entrants are able to satisfy the
every increasing demand for electricity in the region.
</P>
<P>
Only 20 percent of the regions population has access to
electricity.
</P>
<P>
"Due to low tariffs and poor performance of the utilities,
self-financing is generally weak... the foreign debt burdens
facing most developing countries and the fact that the
corporations themselves are heavily indebted makes this route
untenable," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said that governments in the region should open up to allow
private sector participation and commercialization of their
respective power utilities.
</P>
<P>
Chikowore said it was pleasing to note that some governments
in the SADC region have started re-looking at their policies and
reviewing the structures of their utilities with the aim of
improving their performance and mobilizing needed financial
resources for development.
</P>
<P>
At the same meeting, Chief Executive Officer of Zimbabwe
Electricity Supply Authority Simbarashe Mangwengwende said that
demand for electricity was on the increase with the region
expected to use over 307,000 megawatts of electricity by the year
2020 up from the current 26,000 megawatts, most of which is being
consumed by the South African utility, ESKOM.
</P>
<P>
"We, however, need major investments in power generation in
the region and it is also important that decisions be made as
quickly as possible by our respective governments in this area to
ensure we get maximum returns," said Mangwengwende. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
