<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain not Invited to Zimbabwe's Land Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Britain and Germany said Monday
they have not received invitations to participate in the donor
conference on Zimbabwe's land set for June 23 to 25 although they
would be willing to attend.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which is to be a platform for Zimbabwe to
reassure donors that it will conduct its land reform in a
transparent manner, is sponsored by the European Union, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the British High Commission in Harare said his
country was "definitely willing" to attend the conference but had
not received any invitation from the Zimbabwean government.
</P>
<P>
"Once we are invited we will definitely be happy to attend. It
is important for the conference to succeed and our support will
come if land is used for the elimination of poverty," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, so far Britain had not yet seen the
Zimbabwean government's proposals on the land reform exercise.
</P>
<P>
At the German embassy in Harare, a spokeswoman said they had
also not received an invitation to the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference takes place when the Zimbabwean government
having listed over 1,400 farms for acquisition for which
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said the government will only
compensate for improvements and not for the land.
</P>
<P>
Donors have, however, maintained that Zimbabwe's land reform
should be transparent and uphold the rule of law and should
benefit the poor.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Burkina Faso last week, Micheal Camdessus,
managing director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), said
the IMF would support Zimbabwe's land reform if the Zimbabwean
government put in place a system agreeable to all partners.
</P>
<P>
Promises to have resettlement started by June have also fallen
short due to lack of funds for the exercise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
