<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Greece Coordinate on EU Bid: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus held "very intense
coordination" with Greece on its bid to join the European Union
(EU), a government spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Christos Stylianides made the statement at his daily press
briefing here while commenting on the EU summit which opened
Monday in Cardiff, the Welsh capital in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman declined to divulge any details of the
coordination, only saying that the two sides would iron out any
negative development following the recent statements on its EU bid
made by France, which is holding the EU rotatory presidency.
</P>
<P>
A French spokeswoman said last week that a divided Cyprus could
not enter the EU, suggesting the island's accession negotiations
with the EU be postponed.
</P>
<P>
The French statement indicated that France might raise
objections at the Cardiff summit to the continuation of the talks
with Cyprus because the Turkish Cypriots are not participating in
these talks.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said the Cypriot government has taken necessary
steps following the French statement, and is waiting for the
conclusions of the EU summit before making any assessment.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, however, said Cyprus does not have any
information on the possibility of introducing amendments to the
text of matters relating to Cyprus' accession course.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus started its accession talks with the EU in last March
in accordance with a EU summit decision made in December 1997. But
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, who opposed Cyprus' EU
entry, has turned down an invitation from Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides to nominate representatives to participate in the
accession talks as full-fledged members.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
