<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $86 Million British Aid Granted to Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Britain has granted a total of 86
million U.S. Dollars to Angola through the European Union since
1993.
</P>
<P>
Edmund Rich, head of Britain's Department of International
Cooperation, told the Angola News Agency Monday that the grant is
mainly in the areas of education, health, mine-clearing,
humanitarian assistance and the construction of public facilities
in some of the country's provinces.
</P>
<P>
This year, Rich said, Britain will increase its aid in
de-mining, especially in the technical sphere. The main
beneficiary will be Bie Province in central Angola, which had
suffered the hardest during the civil war from 1975 to 1994) with
many land mines planted.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Halo Trust, a non-governmental organization in
Britain, is undertaking the mine-clearing work in the province.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that a British delegation of international
cooperation visited Kuito, capital city of Bie Province, last
Friday to have a on-the-spot inspection on de-mining in the area
so as to introduce new technologies of mine-clearing within the
year.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Angola have enjoyed good relations in the past
years. London has offered aid to Angola during its peace process
in terms of mine-clearing, resettlement of demobilized militiamen
and rehabilitation of infrastructure destroyed by the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
