<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No-confidence Vote against PNA Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) agreed in Ramallah Monday on a 10-day delay for
holding its first no-confidence vote against the Palestinian
self-rule government led by Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The PLC decided to accept Arafat's request for the 10-day delay
"in order to give more time to Arafat to restructure the cabinet,"
the East Jerusalem-based Palestinian news service Jerusalem Media
and Communication Center reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat on Saturday sent a letter to PLC Speaker Ahmed Queria
(Abu Ala), requesting the legislature to delay the vote pending
reshuffle of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) cabinet. The
reshuffle is to be completed by Friday.
</P>
<P>
On May 31, the PLC demanded the PNA further reallocate
the 1998 budget and resubmit it to the legislative body for
approval, or it will face a no-confidence vote in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Arafat promised broad political consultations
with all opposition parties on the reshuffle. He said he was
totally convinced that the cabinet change is part of the necessary
comprehensive administrative improvement of his government.
</P>
<P>
The four-day consultations are expected to start on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some lawmakers have expressed growing dissatisfaction with the
performance of the PNA leadership, charging that it has not
carried out the long-promised reforms despite widespread criticism
of its high-level corruption and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has had promised to reshuffle his cabinet and remove
corrupt ministers, but no real actions have been taken before the
legislators threatened to table the no-confidence motion.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian legislature, formed in January 1996, has a
total of 88 members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
