<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Give Chance to Peace: Ethiopian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Foreign Minister
Seyoum Mesfin said Monday that ''Ethiopia is committed to giving
a chance to efforts to peacefully resolve the crisis, even when
the chances are slim.''
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing Monday afternoon at his ministry, Seyoum
said, "however, Ethiopia reserves the right to take all measures
that it deems appropriate to defend its sovereignty and dignity,
including air strikes which will never target civilians or
civilian institutions."
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the morning, an Ethiopian government spokeswoman
announced here that Ethiopia has agreed with the U.S. government
to temporarily halt air strikes. "We have agreed to an air cease-
fire but if our sovereignty is put under threat we will continue
to defend it," the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton Sunday appealed to Ethiopian Prime
Minister Meles Zenawi to halt air-raids with a view to giving a
chance for peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Seyoum said at the news briefing that ''in accepting the
proposal by friends to suspend further use of air strikes,
Ethiopia has only demonstrated its wish to give the diplomatic
means a chance to deal with the dispute."
</P>
<P>
But, he stressed that "when Ethiopia is convinced that the
peace process has come to an end, it will immediately stop
observing the moratorium on air strikes."
</P>
<P>
Seyoum stressed that Eritrea must immediately and
unconditionally withdraw its forces from occupied areas. He
called for the implementation of the peace proposals submitted by
the U.S. and Rwandan facilitators, saying the peace proposals
"have received the widest possible support of the international
community."
</P>
<P>
Seyoum accused the Eritrean government of unleashing "a
campaign of terror against peaceful Ethiopian civilians residing
in Eritrea."
</P>
<P>
"About 600 are known to the Ethiopian government as having
been imprisoned, tortured and suffering the most inhuman
treatment," he charged, adding, "all over Eritrea, the
authorities have been herding thousands of Ethiopians in camps,
confiscated their property and personal belongings and dumped
them at the border."
</P>
<P>
In his replies to questions, Seyoum said Ethiopian Premier
Meles met and discussed with visiting Italian State Minister of
Foreign Affairs Rino Serri Sunday here on the crisis between
Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the discussion was on whether it is possible for
Ethiopia and Eritrea to declare a moratorium on air strikes, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
