<HEADLINE> Poverty Worsening in Nepal: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The number of Nepalese
living in absolute poverty has nearly doubled in the last two
decades to nine million, according to a U.N. commissioned project.
</P>
<P>
Some 45 percent of Nepal's population of 21 million lives in
poverty and over half the population is malnourished, the U.N.
Development Program (UNDP) quoted Nepal's National Human
Development Report (HDR) as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report, in its weekly news distributed on June 15, also
revealed the sharp disparities in human development indicators
among many districts and regions of the Himalayan Kingdom, with
capital Kathmandu faring the best.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
