<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges Israel to Drop Hardline Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordan, one of the two Arab
countries that have reached peace treaty with Israel, urged the
Jewish state to stop its hardline policy so that peace talks will
be resumed.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister for Development Affairs and
Minister of Foreign Affairs Jawad Anani made the remarks here
Monday after meeting the visiting Australian Parliament Speaker
Ian Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
He said the long-stalled Middle East peace negotiations should
be resumed on all the tracks in accordance with the
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with the delegation that arrived here on
Saturday on a three-day official visit, Anani also said Jordan
does not buy Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's excuses
to evade responsibility for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian-Israeli track of the peace process, Israel
should stop its hardline policy and soon resume talks with the
Palestinians after a 15-month hiatus, Anani told reporters.
</P>
<P>
As to the peace negotiations between Lebanon and Israel,
Jordan supports the Lebanese position and insists that Israel
withdraw from south Lebanon unconditionally in accordance with the
United Nations resolutions 425 and 426, said Anani.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, the Israeli government accepted the resolution 425,
but demanding security guarantees from Lebanese as condition.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have remained deadlocked
since March 1997 due to Jewish settlements expansion in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks were stalled in February 1996,
as Netanyahu's government dropped the former government's promise
to return the Golan Heights Israel seized in the 1967 Mideast
War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
