<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Leaders Agree to Seek Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Burundi
government and all the opposition factions agreed here Monday
afternoon to begin sincere and peaceful talks in a bid to achieve
national reconciliation and end years of bloody conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Burundian President Pierre Buyoya told the opening session
that his government likes to hold talks with all the opposition
factions and hopes this meeting, the first of its kind since he
took power nearly two years ago, will lead to a beginning for
national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
"I appreciate and welcome the support by the neighboring
countries and the international community," he said at the Arusha
International Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from Burundi's major oppositions and parliament also
made their statements, saying they have been tired of endless
bloody conflicts, and hope all the factions should shoulder the
interests of the nation and the people and seek lasting solutions
through sincere and serious talks.
</P>
<P>
Julius Nyerere, the international facilitator and former
Tanzanian president, expressed his thanks for the support from
Burundi, countries in the Great Lakes region as well as the
international community for his mediation.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere's mediation started in late 1996 after seven east and
central African countries imposed economic sanctions on Bujumbura
in August just a few days following a military coup by Major
Buyoya to topple a civilian government led by President S.
Ntibantunganya on July 25.
</P>
<P>
"I hope all the main actors in Burundi will forget the past
and greet a bright future," said the 76-old Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Mkapa, president of Tanzania which is the main
sponsor of the sanctions, told the Burundi leaders that despite
the suffering they brought to the Burundi people, the sanctions
will not be lifted until a genuine national reconciliation is
achieved in the tiny central African country.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni, Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimungu, Zambian Vice President Christon Tembo and Kenyan
Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana all briefed the session which were
attended by some 300 Burundi delegates from various factions,
foreign envoys and representatives of the international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The leaders from countries which are for the sanctions urged
the Burundians to abandon the out-dated military coup and bloody
conflicts and to settle their differences in favor of the nation
and the people.
</P>
<P>
"From our experience, we know that nobody will win in ethnic
genocides and conflicts," President Bizimungu cautioned in his
speech.
</P>
<P>
Messages from the Organization of African Unity Secretary
General Salim Ahmed Salim and the U.N. Chief Kofi Annan were also
presented respectively at the session. The two secretaries
general said in their messages that they were inspired by the
gathering of the Burundi leaders and pledged support to a real
national reconciliation in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi leaders immediately began their talks, mediated by
Nyerere, when the session concluded late in the afternoon while
Buyoya, Museveni, Bizimungu and others left for home.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, Nyerere met separately in Dar es Salaam with
all leaders of the Burundi factions including Leonce
Ngendakumana, the speaker of the National Assembly, Jean-Baptiste
Bagaza and S. Ntibantunganya, Burundi's former presidents, Jean
Minani, the chairman of the Front pour la Democratie an Burundi
(FRODEBU), and Leonard Nyangoma, the chairman of the National
Council for Defense and Democracy (CNDD), as well as Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
They discussed the preparations to make the Arusha talks a
success which may lead to an early lifting of the economic
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
As a gesture to answer the calls by the sanction imposers and
to ease internal tension, Buyoya, an ethnic Tutsi, signed last
week a new transitional constitution and named two vice
presidents including an ethnic Hutu leader from the main
opposition party to replace the Premier.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in
bloody conflicts between the ethnic Hutu majority and the ruling
Tutsi minority since the assassination of Melchior Ndadaye, the
first president elected under a multi-party system in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
