<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams Attempts to Prolong Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Monday accused the United
States and Britain of attempting to prolong sanctions on Iraq by
pressuring the U.N. Security Council to adopt a new resolution on
the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry spokesman was quoted by the Iraqi News
Agency as saying that Washington and London have ignored "the fact
that the oil-for-food program was an exceptional and provisional
deal" between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1996 deal with the U.N., Iraq was allowed to sell 2
billion U.S. dollars worth of oil to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies every six months. The figure was raised
earlier this year to 5.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was commenting on reports that the U.S. is
pushing for indefinitely continuing the program as long as the
economic sanctions, imposed in 1990 after Iraqi invasion of
Kuwait, remain in place.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the U.N. Resolution 687 on the program, in
its third introductory paragraph, emphasizes that the program was
drawn up as a provisional measure, not a permanent one.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S.-British attempt to turn the oil-for-food
program into a permanent one could only be interpreted as their
intention to perpetuate the sufferings of Iraqi people by blocking
the lifting of the trade embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Attacking the U.S. and Britain for pressing other members of
the U.N. Security Council to pass a new resolution on the program,
the spokesman stressed that Iraq holds that "any justification by
the council to pass new resolution is no longer valid."
</P>
<P>
He said the oil-for-food program has obviously failed to ease
the sufferings of Iraqi people as some hoped it would, adding that
it is high time for the U.N. to lift the sanctions since Iraq has
fulfilled all its obligations under the Resolution 687.
</P>
<P>
He urged "all fair and serious-minded members" of the
U.N. Security Council not to succumb to the U.S. and British
pressure and not to allow the draft resolution to be passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
