<HEADLINE> Blair Calls British Soccer Hooliganism "Total Disgrace" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Monday that the hooliganism of British soccer fans in
France was a "total disgrace" to the country.
</P>
<P>
At least 36 were injured when hundreds of soccer fans fought
pitched battles with Tunisian youths and police on Sunday night.
The violence erupted again on Monday during England's match
against Tunisia, and more than 60 people have been arrested --
most of them English -- since Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Fans watching the game on a giant screen on the Marseille
beachfront hurled bottles at one another and at least 15 Tunisians
had been injured by the time the game ended with a 2-0 victory for
England.
</P>
<P>
"The activities of those fans are a total disgrace. They have
nothing whatever to do with the best interests of English football
or our country," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
"I think the whole of the country will unite in condemning
them."
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw also said on Monday the entire nation
had been punished by a "mindless, criminal, drunken minority."
</P>
<P>
Straw told the parliament he had telephoned his French
counterpart Jean-Pierre Chevenement to apologize for the
"disgraceful behavior" of England fans.
</P>
<P>
"I emphasised again our full support for the French police in
dealing swiftly and vigorously with those who cause such
disorder," Straw said.
</P>
<P>
Police and politicians had been hoping for a hooligan-free
World Cup as far as England was concerned after making strenuous
efforts to crack down on soccer-related violence at home and
placing travel restrictions on known trouble-makers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
