<HEADLINE> AIDS Infection Among Swazi Youth Increasing: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- An AIDS survey published in
Swaziland Monday shows that 23 percent of pregnant women and
girls between 15 and 19 years of age are infected with the HIV
virus, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Worst infected are those between 20 and 24 years, of whom 39
percent tested HIV-positive, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
HIV (human immuno-deficiency virus) leads to AIDS (acquired
immuno-deficiency syndome).
</P>
<P>
Swaziland's National AIDS Program manager, Beatrice Dlamini,
warned that the increasing rate of the disease among young people
was undermining all that had been achieved over the years by the
Ministry of Health in increasing life expectancy and reducing
infant mortality.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland, a landlocked southern African country sandwiched
between Mozambique and South Africa has a population of about
900,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
