<HEADLINE> Train Strike Halts 40 Per Cent of Underground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- London travellers are facing
serious travel problems on Monday after a walkout by more than
6,000 London Underground train workers.
</P>
<P>
The strike on the "Tube", called by the Rail Maritime and
Transport (RMT) union over job security dispute, began on Sunday
evening and will run until late on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"About 57 percent of trains are running but that varies line by
line," a London Underground spokesman said, adding that 10
stations had been closed.
</P>
<P>
The Tube criss-crosses the capital, incorporating about a dozen
lines and ferrying hundreds of thousands of people to and from
work every day.
</P>
<P>
"We would be surprised if London Underground would be able to
operate more than a 50 percent service," an RMT spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Long delays on the trains forced many people to take to the
road, causing long traffic jams on most of the major arteries into
the capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
