<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy to Meet Angolan Govt, Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Blondin Beye, United Nations
special envoy in Angola, will meet with Angolan President Eduardo
dos Santos late Monday on the latter's plan for the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Beye will also leave for Andulo city in central Angola this
week to meet with Jonas Savimbi, chairman of the opposition
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), on
the same purpose, Francisco Noguera, an official with the U.N.
observer mission in Angola told the press here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Returning from the U.N. Security Council meeting on Angola,
Beye had called on Angolan government and UNITA, signatories of
the Lusaka Peace Accord in 1994, to redouble efforts to safeguard
peace and security in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution last Friday
imposing new sanctions on the former rebel UNITA movement, which
include freezing UNITA's foreign bank accounts, restricting its
diamond export and limiting UNITA leaders' contacts with any
foreign officials other than the Angolan government and the U.N.
observer mission.
</P>
<P>
The resolution will enter into effect on June 23 if the UNITA
leadership refuses to implement the Lusaka peace deal till then.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Peace Process went into crisis when the UNITA
failed to hand over to the government the four "sensitive areas"
it has occupied in the central part of the country.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the Joint Committee on Angolan Peace Process
Monday on the current crisis confirmed that armed UNITA forces
are mobilizing in a large scale around the country, especially in
the north. The committee was "very worried" over the situation,
said Noguera. 
</P>
</TEXT>
