<HEADLINE> Diamond Mining in Namibia Set to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Namibia could produce 2.25
million carats of diamond a year by the year 2000 should offshore
expansion plans of producers be successful, South African Press
Association quoted the Bank of Namibia as saying.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report for 1997 released Monday, the bank said
offshore diamond mining accounted for 44 percent of Namibia's
overall diamond production, compared to only four percent in
1990.
</P>
<P>
It said the next two years will be crucial in determining the
future of offshore diamond mining.
</P>
<P>
The country's onshore deposits of diamonds could be depleted
within 10 or 20 years, the report said. Growing offshore diamond
production, however, was expected to offset that decline, and
surpass onshore production.
</P>
<P>
It said that over the next few years Namibia would face the
challenges of Angola and Russia in the international diamond
market.
</P>
<P>
However, Namibia was uniquely placed in that it produced high
quality diamonds. Last year's average price for Namibian diamonds
was 315 U.S. Dollars per carat, compared to an average of 230
Dollars for Angolan diamonds, 140 Dollars for Russian gems and
105 Dollars for South African and Botswana diamonds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
