<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Uncovers Missile Launchers on Maltese Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Customs officials Monday
found seven mobile missile launchers suspected as parts of the
Russian-made S-300 missiles for Cyprus on board a Maltese
registered ship they stopped for checking.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency said the ship, named
Natasha-1, was intercepted in the Dardanelles Straits and received
an inspection of its cargo.
</P>
<P>
The Officials uncovered the missile launchers which were not
registered on the list of declaration during the inspection. A
Russian sailor was also found on board.
</P>
<P>
Ships carrying military equipment were required to inform
Turkish authorities of their intention to pass through the
Straits 24 hours before their passage, but no such application
was made by the ship, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said that a careful investigation had to be made to
confirm whether these missile launchers are parts of the S-300
missiles that Russia would deliver to Cyprus under their deal.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior Russian official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, reportedly said in Moscow that these missile launchers
had nothing to do with the S-300 missile deal. "The shipment of
the S-300 missiles has not started yet," he said, declining to
give details.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus clinched a deal with Russia in January 1997 to buy S-300
missiles worth 400 million U.S. dollars in order to increase its
defense capacity.
</P>
<P>
The deal, however, angered Turkey and Turkish Cypriots living
in the northern part of the divided island, who vowed to take all
possible means to prevent the deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since Turkey landed its troops and
took over the northern third in 1974 in the wake of an abortive
coup on the island seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure from the United States and other Western
countries, the Cypriot government has announced that the S-300
missiles will not be deployed until October or November.
</P>
<P>
Despite strong opposition from Ankara, Russia has said that it
will go ahead with the missile deal with Cyprus because this is a
normal arms transaction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
