project to build a steel plant to serve the domestic, Gulf and
Asian markets, the Arabic-language daily Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The UAE Minister of Finance and Industry Sheikh Hamdan Bin
Rashid Al Maktoum said the plant, with an investment of 55 million
dirhams (15 million U.S. dollars), will have a production capacity
of 40,000 metric tonnes of steel materials, three times the
domestic need.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- About 10 percent of the total 5.4 billion U.S. dollars
of foreign investments in Tunisia came from Arab countries,
according to the latest statistics by the Tunisian Ministry of
International Cooperation and External Investments.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the biggest investor, with 490 million dollars,
followed by Kuwait, with 54 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia and the Arab countries have set up 140 joint ventures
in tourism, agriculture, industry and banking, creating 15,000
jobs for Tunisians. 
</P>
