<HEADLINE> Clinton Adviser Criticizes Starr Contacts with Reporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Whitewater Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr was again attacked by the White House after he
admitted in a magazine interview that his office anonymously
provided information to reporters in the Monica Lewinsky probe.
</P>
<P>
White House adviser Rahm Emanuel said the disclosure "goes
right to the heart of the legitimacy" of Starr's work and leaves a
cloud hanging over his office.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published this weekend, Starr admitted he
occasionally, and his deputy frequently, briefed reporters on a
not-for-attribution basis during the five-month investigation.
</P>
<P>
He said neither he nor the deputy, Jackie Bennett, leaked any
improper information, but left open the possibility they may have
provided detail about information they obtained from witnesses
outside the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
Federal law prohibits prosecutors from disclosing information
gathered by the grand jury. The magazine Starr spoke to, Brill's
Content, went on to lash him for "leaking the most damaging
details of the investigation to a willing, eager press corps."
</P>
<P>
Starr said in self-defense Sunday, "We are living up to our
professional responsibilities."
</P>
<P>
The White House has repeatedly accused Starr's office of
leaking sensitive information to the press during the
investigation into whether Clinton had an affair with Ms.
Lewinsky, a former White House intern, and then tried to cover it
up. The president has denied any sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
The president's lawyer has asked a judge to sanction Starr for
alleged leaks. Presidential aides immediately seized on the
article.
</P>
<P>
"These charges are so serious and they go right to the heart of
the legitimacy of the office," Emanuel said Sunday on NBC's "Meet
the Press."
</P>
<P>
At issue for Starr is whether it is also illegal to disclose
what witnesses say outside the room -- such as in interviews with
the FBI or prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
Starr also acknowledged he and his deputy talked to reporters
from The New York Times just before they reported details of what
presidential secretary Betty Currie had told investigators.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
