<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Ten percent of French families own
more than half of the private wealth nationwide, said the official
Council of Taxes on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The council said that the concentration of wealth in a
relatively small number of rich families is an undeniable fact in
France.
</P>
<P>
Private wealth in France in 1996 was estimated at 24,500
billion francs (4,900 billion U.S. dollars), double that in 1970.
</P>
<P>
Half of private wealth are in the hands of those who are
engaged in financial business, it said.
</P>
<P>
Aged people, those who practise independent professions, senior
officials, and people with big incomes are the wealthiest in
France, said the council.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, France is also among the nations which collect the
heaviest income and wealth tax, it added.  
