<HEADLINE> Botha's Case Postponed to August 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president P. W. Botha's trial for snubbing the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) was adjourned Monday until August
17 in the George regional court in Western Cape province.
</P>
<P>
Judgement is likely to be given the following day. If
convicted, Botha could face a jail sentence of up to two years or
a maximum fine of 20,000 Rand (3,770 U.S. Dollars), South African
Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In his closing argument, public prosecutor Bruce Morrison, who
is Western Cape deputy attorney-general, claimed that Botha had
no legal excuse for ignoring a TRC subpoena.
</P>
<P>
Botha, 82, was brought to court after he had repeatedly
rejected the subpoena for hearings on the activities of the
former state security council, which he chaired in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Any objections Botha had to being subpoenaed by the TRC should
have been raised with the TRC itself, Morrison said, adding that
he could have alternatively applied to the high court to set
aside the subpoena or to review the TRC's actions.
</P>
<P>
"He has deliberately done neither. Subpoenas cannot simply be
flouted; they must be set aside by a court on review."
</P>
<P>
Morrison rejected argument by Botha's lawyers that the
subpoena issued against their client was technically invalid.
There was also no truth to the suggestion that there was an
agreement between Botha and TRC chairman Desmond Tutu, which
stated that the former president would not have to testify before
the TRC, he said.
</P>
<P>
Botha made an 1,800-page written submission to the TRC.
</P>
<P>
In their argument, Botha's advocates called for all charges
against Botha to be dropped.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that the subpoena served against Botha was
flawed and the TRC acted in bad faith. 
</P>
</TEXT>
