<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Militia Ready for Resuming Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the Taliban Interim
Council Sheikh Mullah Mohammad Rabbani said here Monday that he is
not against resuming the peace talks with rival forces that broke
off in May.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon his arrival here, Rabbani blamed
Taliban militia's rival, the Northern Alliance, for the failure of
the recent talks held in Islamabad, capital of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He accused the alliance, supported by some foreign countries as
he claimed, of offering conditions that were not in the interest
of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban and the Northern Alliance held their first
face-to-face peace talks in later April, but the talks were
suspended early May due to the sharp differences over the
ceasefire and prisoner swap.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani said the Taliban has no objection to the resumption of
the Afghan peace talks, adding the ball is on the other side's
court. "We left the matter for them to decide on. If they like to
negotiate, we will attend," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani rejected the accusations against the Taliban for
halting the Islamabad talks in order to launch an all-out attack
on the Northern Alliance's military positions. He said that the
Taliban movement supports the peace talks and has showed great
flexibility during the talks.
</P>
<P>
He denied that the Taliban, which is controlling 80 percent of
the country, has created preconditions on the number of the
alliance's representatives to the peace talks in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He also denied that the Islamabad talks were held under a
U.S. mediation. "The Americans have no role in the talks despite
the fact that a U.S. delegation visited Afghanistan during the
talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson, the U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations,
visited Afghanistan last April and reportedly sought to mediate
the peace talks aimed at restoring peace in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani pointed out that the peace talks were sponsored by
Pakistan, in which the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Saudi Arabia
and the Organization of Islamic Conference all played a role.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani arrived here Monday on a four-day visit to UAE. He is
scheduled to hold talks with senior UAE officials on the latest
developments in Afghanistan and the ways of strengthening the
relations between the Taliban and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The UAE recognized the Islamic regime of Taliban last year
after Pakistan and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
