<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Palestinian Bomber Remains in Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian, alleged to be
responsible for a 1982 bombing of an American airliner, was
ordered by a federal judge Monday to remain in jail pending trial.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Attorney Ronald Walutes argued against bail in front of
U.S. District Court Judge Aubrey Robinson on the ground that
Mohammed Rashid, the accused bomber, was dangerous and skilled in
eluding law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
"He has no ties to this country" and would likely flee overseas
if released, Walutes said.
</P>
<P>
He said Rashid was the second-ranking officer in the
Palestinian group known as the 15th of May organization, which was
active in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Rashid, 51, was whisked out of Egypt earlier this month and
brought to Washington to face charges. On June 3, he pleaded
innocent in the bombing of a Pan Am airliner in August 1982, which
killed a Japanese boy and injured 15 other passengers.
</P>
<P>
Rashid has been in jail since his arrival in the United States,
and Robinson ordered him to remain in jail until a trial on nine
charges, including the bombing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
