<HEADLINE> IFC Issues 1998 Edition of Emerging Stock Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation Monday released the 12th edition of its annual
Emerging Stock Markets Factbook, covering markets for 75
developing countries and countries in transition.
</P>
<P>
The factbook tracks the rise and spread of the "Asian
contagion," which was the seminal event for emerging markets in
1997.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, emerging markets had 19,800 listed
companies, representing nearly half of world stock exchange
listings. Their combined market value of 2.3 trillion U.S. dollars
was equivalent to 9 percent of world market capitalization. Six of
the world's 20 largest stock markets were in emerging economies.
More than 2.7 trillion worth of trades were conducted in emerging
markets in 1997, about 14 percent of all world stock trades.
</P>
<P>
The factbook 1998, covering 1997 and earlier years, including
340 pages with chapters on basic economic data and key trends in
capital flows and stock prices, world stock market series,
detailed profiles on individual markets as well as IFC Index
features and results. There is a particular focus on the 52
markets covered in these IFC global, regional and industry indexes
and investable index of stocks available for foreign purchase.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and also the
largest multilateral source for financing private sector projects
in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia FM on Settlement of Kosovo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia favors settling the Kosovo
conflict by peaceful means instead of methods which could worsen
the crisis, the Russian Foreign Ministry stated on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said that it was
necessary to keep from "unilateral, provocative steps that could
push the conflict to escalation."
</P>
<P>
He stressed the international community unanimously agreed the
conflict should be resolved by political methods.
</P>
<P>
Moscow's approach to the Kosovo issue was consistent with its
attitude to the settlement of regional conflicts in the world,
Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
Political measures were required to resolve regional conflicts
that considerably endangered the security and solidarity of the
international community, he said.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday met with visiting
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to discuss the Kosovo
situation.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that Milosevic had agreed to negotiate with ethnic
Albanians in the Serbian province of Kosovo in federal
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
