<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Lanqing Stresses Revitalizing Nation Through Science, Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- China will make science and
technology play a bigger part in forwarding its economic and
social development, and governments at all levels should give
priority to the strategy of revitalizing the nation through
science and education, said Vice-Premier Li Lanqing here today.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of
the Communist Party of China's Central Committee, made the remarks
in a speech delivered at the second session of the Standing
Committee of the Ninth Chinese People's Political Consultation
Conference (CPPCC), which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Li gave an introduction to the government's efforts to carry
out the strategy of revitalizing the nation through science and
education, pointing out the major principles adopted to push
forward China's science and technology development.
</P>
<P>
China will concentrate its efforts on fundamental scientific
research, striving to make breakthroughs in this field, he said,
adding that stress will be put on developing new and high
technologies and their application to industry.
</P>
<P>
Li emphasized that structural reform of the scientific and
technological systems should be deepened, and compulsory education
should be spread nationwide among young people to eliminate
illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China will strenuously develop vocational education,
build several universities into first-level ones in the world and
form the basic framework for a new higher-education management
structure, he said.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels should guarantee that the increase of
financial input into science and education will be bigger than
that of financial income, and part of the extra-budget income
should also be put into science and education, Li stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Calls on European Nations to Curb Hooliganism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- International soccer body FIFA called
for concerted efforts from the European countries to prevent the
spilling of hooliganism into the World Cup finals here.
</P>
<P>
"FIFA is not a police organization, we don't control frontiers, but
we would like to see measures taken to prevent troublemakers from
leaving their country at the time of important football competitions
elsewhere," FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "The hooligan problem in England is largely contained.
Problems occur when the English team are playing in another country
and that's why we would like to see the British government and the
European authorities take measures or strengthen existing laws."
</P>
<P>
Three English fans have been jailed for their role in riots at
Marseille before Monday's World Cup game between England and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
However, Cooper said the English Football Association could be held
responsible for the behavior of English fans.
</P>
<P>
"FIFA has always been very satisfied with cooperation with the
English F.A. and there is no discussion of England being expelled from
this tournament or not being able to enter the 2002 World Cup."
</P>
<P>
CFO president Michel Platini, also commentng on the Marseille
violence, said he felt there would no longer be problems at England's
next matches against Romania on June 22 and against Colombia on June
26. 
</P>
