<HEADLINE> Singapore, Malaysia to Conduct Joint Air Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore and Malaysia will
conduct a joint air defense exercise (ADEX) in the airspace over
Peninsular Malaysia and Singapore from June 17 to 18, the
Singapore Ministry of Defense (MiD) announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
MiD said the exercise, codenamed MINOR ADEX 98-3, is to be held
within the framework of the Five Power Defense Arrangements (FPDA)
which comprises Australia, Malaysia, New Zealand, Singapore and
the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The Headquarters Integrated Air Defense System (HQ IADS),
located at the Royal Malaysia Air Force (RMAF) base in
Butterworth, will serve as the coordination center for the
exercises and Air Vice-Marshal R. B. Treloar, commander of the HQ
IADS, will be the exercise director.
</P>
<P>
MINOR ADEX 98-3 is designed to increase the capability of the
air defense forces of the two FPDA member nations to preserve the
integrity of the Malaysian and Singapore airspace against a
simulated external air threat, MiD said.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, the aircraft and air defense
units assigned to take part in the two-day exercise include the
F-5, F-16, A4-SU, MiG-29, Hawk, C-130, KC-130, Fokker 50,
Beechcraft, Cessna, Ground-based air defense radar units,
surface-to-air missiles and anti-aircraft artillery.
</P>
<P>
MINOR ADEX 98-3 is the third maneuver of this kind this year.
MINOR ADEX 98-1 was conducted in March, followed by the MAJOR ADEX
98-2 that was held in April on a larger scale with the
participation of all five FPDA member nations' air and maritime
forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
