<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't Not to Step in Airline's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Tuesday that it will not intervene in a massive retrenchment
program of the debt-ridden and strike-bound Philippine Airlines
(PAL) which will affect some 5,000 employees Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We can not just interfere in the internal affairs of that
private corporation although the government is a minority
stockholder there," Executive Secretary Alexander Aguirre told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Aguirre justified the PAL decision to fire the 5,000
employees, about 40 percent of its 13,700-strong workforce, saying
it is better to see the unemployment of 5,000 than that of 15,000.
</P>
<P>
PAL announced Monday that it has started to retrench 5,000
employees as part of a survival plan after an 11-day pilots'
strike brought the flag carrier to its knees.
</P>
<P>
PAL, which already issued walking papers to some 100 employees
Monday, said the retrenchment was covered by its collective
bargaining agreement (CBA) with its employees.
</P>
<P>
The retrenchment was triggered off by the ongoing crippling
strike by its 620 pilots who accused the management of invoking a
forced retirement policy in the CBA.
</P>
<P>
PAL, whose long-term debts alone amounted to nearly 10 billion
pesos (244 million U.S. dollars) as of March this year, fired all
the striking pilots and blamed the pilots' strike for plunging
into a deeper hole.
</P>
<P>
The airline said the cutbacks would allow it to recover
financially and to turn the airline into a more efficient
operation.
</P>
<P>
The airline said it has lost over 2 billion pesos (48 million
dollars) since the 620-strong pilots' union walked out on June 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
