<HEADLINE> GCC Oil Ministers Begin Talks on Output Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Oil ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) started their 21st session Tuesday
afternoon in Saudi capital Riyadh to unify stance on helping push
up oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are discussing production cuts and the situation
on the world oil market, the Kuwait News Agency quoted sources
close to the meeting as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are on their way to determine the reduction of
their shares, the sources said. But he did not give further
details.
</P>
<P>
The GCC ministerial meeting came amid moves by members and
non-members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) to further slash their output in an effort to shore up oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
The world oil prices slumped to nine-year lows in March due to
oversupply and the sagging demand, especially in southeast Asia
because of the financial turmoil there.
</P>
<P>
Major oil producers trimmed their output in April, trying to
boost oil prices. But their move has so far apparently failed to
help the oil market out.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and non-OPEC Mexico clinched a deal on
June 4 to decide to reduce their output by 450,000 barrels per day,
kicking off a fresh round of production cut.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates,
Qatar, Bahrain and Oman, whose economy depends heavily on oil
earnings.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the GCC ministerial meeting will also
tackle a string of joint projects, including a natural gas network
in the region, and explore ways to boost gas trade with European
Union member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
