<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Urges Japan, U.S. to Act on Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong leader Tuesday urged
Japan and the United States to take quick actions to stabilize the
yen, which has recently plunged to an 8-year low of 146 to one
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
In a media session after the Executive Council meeting, acting
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
Donald Tsang said here that the great volatility in the yen and
the U.S. dollar exchange rate has affected the economic
performance across the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
"We must urge the leading economies, particularly Japan and
America, to come forward to stabilize the situation. It is not
doing anybody any good at all," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The weakening of the Japanese yen has put pressure on the Hong
Kong dollar, pushing up interbank interest rates in Hong Kong over
the last few days.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said: "Continued volatility in the yen exchange rate
means that interest rates are likely to be higher than normal in
Hong Kong, and we still have to be very alert to what is happening
around us."
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed the government's commitment to the linked
exchange rate system, under which the Hong Kong currency is pegged
to the greenback at 7.8 HK dollars to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"It (the peg) is not going to change," he said, adding "in
fact moving the linked exchange rate now will create immediate
chaos and will bring havoc to the economy."  
</P>
</TEXT>
