<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, US Scientists to Cooperate on Frontiers of Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- China and the US will jointly
sponsor a "symposium on sciences at the frontier" in the US in
August to promote the cooperation between the two countries' young
scientists, said Xu Zhihong, vice-president of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS) here today.
</P>
<P>
CAS will select 60 outstanding young scientists from all over
the country to attend the symposium and discuss with their US
counterparts some hot scientific issues, such as using space
technology in geoscience, reducing natural disasters, protecting
water resources and analyzing the global climate.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that there is a harmonious atmosphere for cooperation
among scientists in some Western countries, where debates and
competitions are also encouraged. But such a good atmosphere for
scientific development has not yet been formed in China.
</P>
<P>
"The exchange and cooperation in sciences at the frontier with
American scientists may help Chinese young scientists learn
advanced experience in scientific development, such as
trans-subject cooperation and reform their traditional working
style," he said.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, the first of its kind for the two countries,
will be held once a year alternatively in China and in the United
States in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges and cooperation between the two countries have
developed rapidly since an agreement on scientific and
technological cooperation was signed in 1979, Xu said, adding that
CAS has participated in projects concerning high-energy physics,
and studies in basic science and global greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
He said such cooperation has improved the training of
high-tech personnel, especially young scientists in China. CAS has
sent 10,000 people to the United States to work and study, making
up one quarter of the total number of people sent abroad.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Academy of Sciences is to devote most of the
financial resources used for its international exchanges to
sponsor programs that bring together the most outstanding young
scientists of the two countries, who represent the future leaders
in science and technology in China and the United States,
according to Dr. Bruce Alberts, president of the academy.
</P>
<P>
"We view this as an important investment for the future of
science as well as for the future of a friendly and cooperative
relationship between our two countries," he explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
