<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Maybe Understate External Debt: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has called the attention of the Philippines' monetary
authorities for "understating" its external liabilities, the
Central Bank of the Philippines said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, in a report following its recent review of the
country's balance of payments and external debt statistics, noted
the need for the central bank to further expand its monitoring
system to include other loan transactions and other external
obligations which are not registered with the central bank.
</P>
<P>
According to the IMF, the non-inclusion of such external debts
results in an understatement of the country's true external debt
situation.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said the published external debt statistics appear to
be understated by 6 billion U.S. dollars. The central bank has
reported that as of end-1997, the country's external obligations
amounts to 45.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the central bank, in a statement issued Tuesday, tried to
downplay the IMF's observation.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said there was some slight difference in the
central bank's figures compared to those of the Bank for
International Settlements (BIS) and the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
The central bank explained that slightly higher BIS figures for
the country's short-term debt was admitted to be attributable to
differences in classification of certain accounts under the BIS
and Philippine systems.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines had been previously criticized by the
international community during the Marcos administration in the
early 1980s when former central bank governor Jaime Laya
sanctioned an understatement of the country's foreign debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
