<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Little Changed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
little changed Tuesday, at one point touching a new 12-year low of
58 U.S. cents before soaring as high as 59.05 U.S. cents as it was
dragged into the wake of a volatile Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
However, the currency closed the local session only marginally
stronger at 58.68 U.S. cents, from 58.59 U.S. cents in Sydney late
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia Treasury Manager Paul Macarounas said it
had been a "wild day" with most of the action in the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
"But the Australian dollar is basically back into neutral
ground," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese unit was pushed and pulled Tuesday as market
participants assessed the likelihood of the Bank of Japan (BOJ)
rushing to the rescue of its ailing currency.
</P>
<P>
Macarounas said Tuesday's solid end result for the Australian
dollar was likely to be only temporary as the bad news prevailed.
</P>
<P>
"All the negative factors are still in the market and the
Aussie (dollar) will continue to struggle," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will more likely see it test the record post-float low of
0.5710 U.S. dollar sometime in the near future," he said.
</P>
<P>
The currency reached that low on July 28, 1986.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Banking Corp. General Manager Bill Evans said the
Australian dollar was likely to push down toward the 0.5500 U.S.
dollar level before making any sustainable recovery.
</P>
<P>
Evans said there might be some temporary consolidation towards
the 0.5900 U.S. dollar level, but there was little relief in sight
on the Asian and commodity price woes that have seen the
Australian dollar lose 4.3 U.S. cents over the past month and 7.2
U.S. cents since the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile on the cross rates, the Australian dollar was also
buying 85.52 Japanese yen from 85.41 yen at Monday's close and
1.0588 German marks from 1.0614 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
