<HEADLINE> Philippine Police Chief Says Will Not Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine National Police (PNP)
Director General Santiago Alino said on Tuesday that he would not
submit any courtesy resignation as head of the national police
force to president-elect and Vice President Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Alino was quoted by the official Philippine News Agency as
saying that although Estrada had the prerogative to designate a
new PNP chief, he would not submit a courtesy resignation, unless
he is ordered officially to do so by the incoming new
administration.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, the main opposition candidate who won the May 11
presidential poll, will be sworn in as the next president on June
30 to replace outgoing President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Under the related law, the position of the PNP chief has a
maximum term of four years and a compulsory retirement age of 56.
</P>
<P>
Alino, whose retirement age is yet in 2000, explained that it
would be the prerogative of the new president to replace him with
his choice.
</P>
<P>
"It's too early to submit a courtesy resignation. I have to
wait first for the decision of the newly elected president," Alino
said.
</P>
<P>
Alino said that in case he would submit a courtesy resignation,
he would still remain active in the police service.
</P>
<P>
The position of the PNP chief is not co-terminus with the
tenure of the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
