<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholars Say Expanding Education Can Solve Unemployment Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese sociologists have urged
that education be expanded to help solve the problem of
unemployment, which is acute in the country.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences says
that if the number of students enrolled by colleges and secondary
professional schools would be increased by 50 percent, and that if
the policy would be adhered to for three to four years, the
timetable for several million young people to enter the labor
market will be effectively postponed.
</P>
<P>
And the increase of the number of students means more job
opportunities, the report says, explaining that the lack of
skilled workers is a major factor to trigger unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Chinese state-owned enterprises witnessed more than
six million laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
There are 25 college graduates in 10,000 people on average in
China, and the rate is very low compared with developed countries
and many developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The report says that the current policy of rejuvenating China
through science and education requires the development of colleges
and other schools.
</P>
<P>
It adds that in industrialized countries educational and
scientific sectors have become key industries to attract new
labors.
</P>
<P>
In urban areas, the expenditure in education has taken a big
proportion in Chinese citizens' consumption structure, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
The major problem is that the underdeveloped education can not
satisfy people's demands of entering schools, the report points
out. It urges the government to reform the educational mechanism
established under a planned economy and to set up more schools
through various means, including private channels.
</P>
<P>
But the report doesn't say how to help college students find a
job. Statistics from the Education Ministry show that some 20
percent of college graduates this year are still waiting for jobs.
</P>
<P>
And more experts have said that education will not be
effectively developed if the overall economy can not become strong
enough. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Vows to Strengthen Securities Market Supervision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- China will make continued efforts
to enhance supervision over its fledging securities market to
ensure stability and reduce risks, a senior securities industry
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"We will further strengthen our supervision over securities
institutions in areas such as assets, trading practices,
personnel, venues and equipment, to protect the interests of the
investors," Geng Liang, vice-chairman of the China Securities
Regulatory Commission (CSRC), said at a meeting sponsored by the
Securities Association of China.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a unified supervisory system has been
established, as the People's Bank of China, the central bank, has
transferred its functions and responsibilities relating to the
securities market to the CSRC, the industry watchdog.
</P>
<P>
While the majority of Chinese securities institutions have over
the years scored considerable successes in business
standardization and expansion, some of them have accumulated a
large amount of bad assets due to poor management, with still
others having violated rules and engaging in speculation, Geng
said.
</P>
<P>
Official figures indicate that China currently has 327
securities institutions, which have a total of 2,440 operations
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee effective market supervision, the authorities will
combine on-the-spot supervision with other types of supervision,
with the focus on securities institutions with poor-quality assets
and great risk exposure, Geng said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the securities institutions to exercise
self-discipline, which is of special significance for the
high-risk securities industry.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 representatives from securities institutions
across China are participating in the two-day meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to See Huge Revenue Loss in Currency Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government may post
a 40-billion-peso (976 million U.S. dollars) loss in revenue in
1998 following the renewed fall of the Philippine peso against the
green back, Finance Secretary Salvador Enriquez said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Enriquez said the outgoing
Ramos administration will likely leave the next government with a
cash budget deficit of close to 15 billion pesos (365 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
As of end-May, Enriquez said, the cash budget position of the
government continued to register a deficit of 15.5 billion pesos
(378 million dollars), much higher than the programmed deficit for
the five-month period of only 75 million pesos (1.8 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government led by President Fidel Ramos has promised to
leave 1 billion pesos (24 million dollars) in budget surplus by
June 30 when it hands over the reins of government to
president-elect Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez said that the renewed currency turmoil fueled by the
sharp fall of the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar has further
eroded revenue sources such as those collected by the Bureau of
Customs and to some extent by the Bureau of External Revenue.
</P>
<P>
On Monday when the yen plunged against the dollar, the peso
depreciated by more than 5 percent to a low of 42.45 to one
dollar. The peso was traded at an average of 41.77 to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez said the International Monetary Fund is aware of the
government's position and is not likely to take it against the
country in completing the review of the Philippines' economic
performance under a new loan program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
