<HEADLINE> Iraqi Vice President Leaves for Yemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan left here Tuesday for Sanaa to pay a visit to Yemen as
special envoy of Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan told the Iraqi News Agency before departure that during
his visit, he would deliver a letter from Saddam to Yemeni
President Ali Abdullah Saleh.
</P>
<P>
The letter centers on bilateral relations and Iraq's ties with
the United Nations Security Council and the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) charged with overseeing the elimination of
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
It also touchs on Iraqi people's sufferings and its cause - the
eight-year-old harsh international economic sanctions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq says it has carried out all the relevant U.N. Security
Council resolutions and calls for lifting of the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Only when the UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has destroyed all the
banned weapons will the U.N. Security Council lift the sanctions
imposed on the country in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan said he would also discuss with Yemeni officials the
situation in the Arab world and issues of common interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
