<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14,200 African Refugees Living in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 14,200 refugees from
other African countries are staying in Angola, dependent on
government relief and assistance, a senior Angolan official said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Assistance and Social Reintegration
Eufrazina Maiato made the remarks at a press conference marking
the Day of African Refugees whcih falls on June 20.
</P>
<P>
Maiato said that of the 14,000 refugees staying in Angola,
11,800 are from the Democratic Republic of Congo, 2,320 from
Rwanda and 150 from Burundi. They fled to Angola from civil war
in their own countries.
</P>
<P>
Maiato said that the Angolan government is seeking every
possible ways to help these refugees, though the prolonged civil
war in Angola also created a large number of internal refugees
who are in urgent need for relief.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the Angolan government has worked with the
Office of the Representative of United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees in offering relief in time to the refugees from the
three African countries to help them to survive the hardest
times.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the repatriation of the Angolan refugees staying
in other countries, she said that her ministry is working
actively in a bid to help the 300,000 refugees to return within
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Assistance and Social Reintegration is
focusing on removing the land mines in the areas where the
refugees are to be rehabilitated, setting up reception centers
for returning refugees, reconstructing the infrastructures in the
refugee communities and rebuilding roads leading to the original
living places of the refugees, the deputy minister said.
</P>
<P>
During the nearly 20 years of civil war, a total number of
three million Angolan became refugees, 700,000 of whom fled
abroad.
</P>
<P>
So far, only 100,000 Angolan refugees have returned home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
