<HEADLINE> Blatter Supports African Bid for 2006 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- FIFA president Sepp Blatter gave his
support to an African bid for the 2006 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
It served as a blow to England's chances of World Cup bid
campaign, especially after two day violence caused mainly by England
hooligans at Marseille.
</P>
<P>
"An African country would have a very strong chance of
winning the right to hold 2006," Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said that as long as the country met the standards set
down by FIFA, then the sport's world governing body would favor an
African host for the 2006 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
There are only three serious contenders for the 2006 World
Cup--England, Germany and South Africa. Australia has just
expressed its interest of luanching a bid for the tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
