<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Stock markets plummeted in the United States and around the
world Monday as Asia's economic troubles deepened, prompting
urgent international calls for Japan to shore up its economy and
stave off a possible global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
-- The roars of high-flying fighter jets rolled over the
mountains of Albania Monday as the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) staged a five-hour show of force aimed at
ending Serbia's military crackdown in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Two studies found that despite the U.S. economy's robust
growth, low-income families continued to face record-level
problems in the most basic of economic transactions: paying the
rent.
</P>
<P>
-- The Nuclear Regulatory Commission said safety conditions had
sufficiently improved at the Millstone nuclear power plant in
Connecticut for it to be restarted.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- China joined the U.S. and Western Europe in pressing Japan
to reform its economy and boost its currency, but Tokyo showed no
sign of taking action. Meanwhile, the yen dropped further.
</P>
<P>
-- Microsoft and Compaq invested 212.5 million dollars apiece
in the Road Runner service of Time Warner and MediaOne. Each will
take a ten percent stake, betting on the cable industry's ability
to sell high-speed Internet access. 
</P>
</TEXT>
