<HEADLINE> Austrian Coach Willing to Be Underestimated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SAINT-ETIENNE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Austrian coach said he was
willing his team being underestimated before Wednesday's match
against Chile.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian team were lucky enough to get a point in the match
against Cameroon while the Chileans were denied a win by the
Nigerian referee who awarded a controvsial penalty to the Italian
team.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody likes to be considered second best, but in football it
has its advantages," said Austrian coach herbert Prohaska.
</P>
<P>
"I hope they think we are the underdogs," said Prohaska, "The
possibility of winning grows when you're underestimated."
</P>
<P>
The Chilean team will be in their full strength again in the
Wednesday's match as their ace striker Marcelo Salas has recovered
from a thigh strain.
</P>
<P>
Salas scored twice in the match against Italy which eventually
ended with a 2-2 draw.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian team will also be without injury problem by the
time of match kick-off. Defender Wolfgang Feiersinger and
midfielder Heimo Pfeiffenberger, who suffered minor injuries, are
both expected to be fit again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
