<HEADLINE> Philippines Urges Japan to Prop up Asian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Finance Secretary
Salvador Enriquez Tuesday urged Japan to help prop up the Asian
economy by buying more exports of its regional neighbors which are
being affected by the new round of currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez made this appeal as the Philippine peso, which
followed the weakening Japanese yen to fall against the U.S.
dollar Monday, continued to remain weak against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the Philippine Dealing System, the peso regained strength
against the dollar Tuesday as the yen managed to appreciate. The
peso, which once fell to a low of 42.58 pesos to one dollar, was
traded at an average of 41.77 pesos to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign exchange traders said the market was still
jittery due to the unstable yen.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez said the "vulnerable" yen is the new "stimulus" to the
new round of Asian currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Japanese authorities to revise their economic
orientation by opening up their market to exports from its
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez said that Japan has always protected its own economy
and not tried to take the lead in ensuring the economic strength
of its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
This time around, he said, Japan should help revive the economy
of the region by purchasing more exports of its neighbors, thus
propping up their economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
