<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyundai Group Founder Enters DPRK on Foot by Crossing MDL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korean business tycoon Chung
Ju-Yung Tuesday morning entered the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) by crossing the Military Demarcation Line (MDL) on
foot at the truce village of Panmunjon.
</P>
<P>
"I am so happy to visit my hometown. I am so happy to go to my
birthplace in my car," said the 83-year-old founder of Hyundai
Group, who was born in what is now the DPRK's Tongchon, before he
crossed the MDL with his donation of 500 head of cattle loaded on
50 Hyundai trucks.
</P>
<P>
He had offered to donate a total of 1,000 head of cattle and
50,000 tons of maize to the DPRK. The rest of the donation will be
delivered after consultations on the route and schedule between
the Red Cross organizations of the two sides complete.
</P>
<P>
Supported by his sons, Chung went into one of the small blue
huts straddling the MDL at 10 a.m. (local time), and set foot on
DPRK soil, where a line of females in their Sunday-best welcomed
him with bouquets.
</P>
<P>
When Chung crossed middle line of the hut into the DPRK, a DPRK
official was heard saying, "You are really very welcome."
</P>
<P>
Outside, both U.S. and South Korean troops lining on the
southern side of the huts and DPRK soldiers on the northern side
witnessed the historic event.
</P>
<P>
Chung is the first South Korean businessman to have entered the
DPRK via Panmunjon, the place of tension and confrontation, a half
century after the division of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Before this event, Panmunjon had never been used as a route for
the intra-Korean private visits and transportation of commodities.
</P>
<P>
Chung, who had made another trip to the DPRK in 1989, said his
current visit was aimed at exploring tourism resources at Mountain
Kumkang and economic cooperation prospects.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary on the event issued Tuesday, the South Korean
Ministry of Unification said Chung's visit and donation are of
great significance as the use of Panmunjon, as a channel of
private visits and commodity transportation, will bring about an
atmosphere of reconciliation and cooperation and an opportunity
for confidence building.
</P>
<P>
"The Republic of Korea government hopes the intra-Korean
exchange through Panmunjon will grow, " said the ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
