<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Confirms Further Cut in Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
Tuesday confirmed that it will further cut its oil production in
support of the Amsterdam agreement signed by other three major oil
producers earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
UAE Minister of Petroleum and Mineral Resources Obeid bin Saif
Al Nasir made the confirmation before his departure Tuesday
for Riyadh, Saudi Arabia to attend the meeting of the ministerial
petroleum cooperation committee of the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) member states, due to start later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the UAE will announce the scope of its
cut in oil production following consultations with other oil
producing countries in and out of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
The UAE had decided to cut petroleum production by 125,000
barrels per day as from April 1, in the wake of the Riyadh accord
signed by Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico on March 22 to
bolster up petroleum prices in the world market.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed his country's support for the Amsterdam accord
signed by the three countries on June 4 to cut their oil
production by 450,000 barrels per day as from July 1.
</P>
<P>
The UAE minister spelt out the necessity of reaching agreement
at the OPEC meeting on June 24 in Vienna on the scope of
production cuts.
</P>
<P>
On the Riyadh meeting, he said it will examine the conditions
of the world market in the light of the current developments in
petroleum prices and coordination among GCC member states in
support of the Amsterdam accord.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
