<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close 1.6 Percent Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A big slump on Wall Street
overnight combined with Asia worries and a bouncing Aussie dollar
wiped 1.6 percent off the Australian share market Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index ended 42.6 points lower at
2524.9, off an intra-day low of 2511.2, as local sentiment
remained fragile.
</P>
<P>
"It's the same scenario that's hung over the market for the
last month or so -- Wall St. came back overnight, there's ongoing
concerns over Asian markets and the performance of the Aussie
dollar," Shaw Stockbroking's Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index shed 58 points to 4423.7 while the
resources sector tumbled 32.9 points or 3.2 percent to 994.1 on
the back of weaker metal prices.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications giant Telstra Corp managed to defy the trend
after its chief executive Frank Blount said it had been approached
by Microsoft boss Bill Gates over a possible equity joint venture
in Telstra's broadband network. The stock added nine cents to 3.73
Australian dollars on hefty volume of 21.69 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Australia's financial services heavyweight AMP shares settled
2.50 Australian dollars lower to 20.50 Australian dollars
following their stunning debut Monday when they listed at 35.99
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the stock is still trading above its true value
based on fundamental analysis of the company.
</P>
<P>
The AMP topped trade Tuesday, with more than 24.27 million
shares changing hands worth 291 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP ended 44.2 cents worse at 12.678 Australian
dollars, Rio Tinto dropped 65 cents to 18.40 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index clawed back some of its earlier losses to finish
25.3 points softer at 1038.3. The price of the precious metal
weakened overnight but was firmer in late afternoon trade locally.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion was trading 1.80 U.S. dollars an
ounce better at 286.20 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector was mixed, with the index dipping 15.7
points to 5526.0. National Australia Bank fell five cents to 21.35
Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia firmed 4.2
cents to 17.55 Australian dollars, Westpac bank rose five cents
to 9.45 Australian dollars and ANZ bank came off 10 cents to 10.40
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover hit 368.48 million worth 915.4 million U.S.
dollars, with falls outpacing rises 811 to 453. 
</P>
</TEXT>
