<HEADLINE> Japan to Push For Pak-Indian Talks on Kashmir: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Japan is determined to pursue
its initiative to push for a Pakistan-India meeting in Tokyo for a
solution to the Jammu and Kashmir dispute though it has been
rejected by India, said Japanese Ambassador Minoru Kubota here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kubota made the remarks when he called on Pakistani Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan on his return from Tokyo after
consultation with his government on the situation arising from the
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan last month, according to a
press release issued by the Pakistani Foreign Office Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Kubota informed Gohar that the Japanese people and government
are fully aware of the compulsions behind Pakistan's explosions
and are convinced that the root cause of the tensions in South
Asia must be addressed as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his meeting with Japanese business leaders,
he urged them to not only continue but to increase their
investment in and trade with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said although Japan's initiative for a Pakistan-India
meeting on the Jammu and Kashmir issue was rebuffed by India, his
government is determined to pursue it.
</P>
<P>
Gohar appreciated the Japanese concern about the peace and
security situation in South Asia and stressed the need for finding
a solution to the Kashmir problem through international mediation.
</P>
<P>
He urged an early ratification of the Investment Protection
Agreement signed by Pakistan and Japan in Tokyo in March this
year.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Japan and other countries to lift the sanctions
imposed on Pakistan for its nuclear tests in late May in response
to those by India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
