<HEADLINE> Zambian President Asks Ruling Party's National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has told national chairman of the Ruling Movement for
Multi-Party Democracy (MMD), Sikota Wina, together with his
treason accused wife princess Nakatindi to immediately resign
from the MMD National Executive Committee (NEC), the Post
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Chiluba as asking them to quit NEC
for disclosing the financial support by detained former Finance
Bank chairman Rajan Mahtani to MMD 1996 presidential and
parliamentary election campaign.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting last week Chiluba asked Wina why he disclosed the
matter to the media, according to the Post.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba gave Wina Tuesday (today) as the deadline to hand in
his resignation letter.
</P>
<P>
Wina told the Post last week that Chiluba and MMD were given
1.5 billion Kwacha for the 1996 election campaign by Mahtani.
</P>
<P>
Nakatindi has been detained on a charge of involvement in the
October 28 failed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
