<HEADLINE> Zambia Nets $660,000 from Tobacco Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has netted over 660,000
U.S. Dollars this year from tobacco sales but prices are lower
than expected, according to Financial Mail.
</P>
<P>
The Tobacco Association of Zambia officials said that about
half a million kilograms of Virginia tobacco have been sold at
the Lusaka auction floor at the total value of about 636,000
Dollars at an average price of 1.2 dollars per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
As much as 24,000 kilograms of Barley tobacco were sold with a
value of 27,000 Dollars at an average price of 1.13 Dollars per
kilogram.
</P>
<P>
However, the country tobacco farmers expected this year's
tobacco prices to be 10 percent higher than last year and fear
that the low prices may tempt the emerging farmers who have since
diversified into tobacco growing to either cut back on output or
abandon the venture altogether, the weekly newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the farmers said production cost of tobacco now at one
Dollar per kilogram gives them negligible profit margins at
current tobacco sales and only hoped that prices do increase to
avoid a likely reduction in tobacco production in the 1998/99
season.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zimbabwe, the third largest tobacco exporter after
Brazil and the United States, initially recorded low tobacco
prices but its prices have now risen to 1.58 Dollars per kilogram
as at last Thursday, 0.29 Dollars less than expected 1.87
Dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
