<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Mortality Remains High in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Despite the efforts being made to
fight HIV/AIDS in Africa, the mortality and morbidity rates of
the pandemic remain high in the continent, the World Health
Organization (WHO) has said.
</P>
<P>
Regional WHO Director for Africa Ephraim Samba was quoted by
Times of Zambia as saying here Monday that Africa with only 10
percent of the world population currently has 70 percent of the
20.8 million global cases of the HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"Every country on the continent has to a lesser or larger
degree reported cases of HIV/AIDS which every day infects 7,500
Africans out of the global total of 16,000 daily infections," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Samba said by the end of 1997 about nine million adults and
1.5 million children have developed AIDS in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Of these about seven million children and adults were said to
have already died.
</P>
<P>
He said the most vulnerable groups have been from Africa's
most active and productive people aged between 15 to 40 years.
</P>
<P>
"The results have been a weakening productive base, a growing
orphan population, further strains on already under-staffed and
under-funded health service across the continent and the adverse
consequences of all these on the quality of life of Africans,"
Samba said.
</P>
<P>
Factors accounting for this grim situation include the wide
practice of unprotected sex, high fertility, high incidence of
sexually transmitted diseases and poor access to care and
information, said Samba.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
