<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Official Warns of Harms of Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The computer's year 2000 problem
poses a real challenge as only 18 months are left to deal with it
before the immutable deadline, a Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) official warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The year 2000 problem can lead to potentially disastrous
results if not properly addressed," Deputy Secretary for
Information Technology and Broadcasting Jessie Ting said. "In a
worst case scenario, it could cause a complete shutdown of all the
operations. So don't leave anything to chance."
</P>
<P>
"The sooner you get started with your year 2000 project, the
sooner potential problems can be identified and actions taken to
avert them. The key is: act now," she said.
</P>
<P>
Ting was speaking at a seminar on the year 2000 problem and its
implications for buildings, facilities and security systems
organized by Hongkong Institute of Engineers and International
Facility Management Association (Hong Kong Chapter) here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The seminar provides a useful forum for experts of different
disciplines to discuss with buildings and facilities managers how
the year 2000 problem should be tackled in a holistic manner, she
said. "It drives home the message that the year 2000 problem is
not just a technical problem which can be left to the technicians
to resolve."
</P>
<P>
Safeguarding operational continuity is the prime driving force
behind the SAR government's comprehensive year 2000 compliance
program, which aims to avoid any disruption in the delivery of
public services when the new millennium arrives, Ting said.
</P>
<P>
And a high-level inter-departmental steering committee on the
issue has been set up and it has drawn up a three-pronged approach
to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
Ever since late 1996, year 2000 compliance requirement has been
included in all the new procurement of IT systems and equipment of
the government, Ting noted.
</P>
<P>
For all those systems and equipment which were put in place or
acquired before late 1996, a comprehensive rectification and
replacement program has been embarked to ensure year 2000
compliance. Every department has now developed a year 2000
rectification plan and action timetable, with progress being
closely monitored by the steering committee, according to Ting.
</P>
<P>
At present, she said, over 50 percent of the government's
existing systems and equipment are already year 2000 compliant and
the remainder are expected to achieve compliance well within 1999.
</P>
<P>
A series of publicity programs have been worked out to promote
awareness and encourage businesses in the private sector to take
early action.
</P>
<P>
The world faces an extremely tight time frame for dealing with
the year 2000 implications for embedded systems, which are the
core concern of buildings and facilities managers, she said. "We
have to work closely with the suppliers or manufacturers both in
assessing and fixing the problem." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Companies Hesitant to Commit to Public Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A new study shows that big
companies are still hesitant to commit to public Internet because
of concerns about its reliability and security.
</P>
<P>
Without a common set of specifications, technologies and
products which guarantee a level of security and reliability
businesses require, the Internet may simply become an interesting
public access network, International Data Corp.(IDC) said in a
report released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The information technology market researcher surveyed an
unidentified number of multinational corporations, including those
in retail, financial services, telecommunications, computer
equipment and mail-order industries. Each of them employed more
than 19,000 workers, with average annual revenues of 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, there has been a tremendous return on
investment for companies that have developed intranets, in-house
Web sites that serve the employees of the enterprises, and
extranet, Web sites for existing customers rather than the general
public, to reduce costs and increase productivity. Meanwhile, new
revenues have been realized by companies pioneering Internet
commerce.
</P>
<P>
But the findings also indicate that the phenomenal business
growth in the Internet may plateau because of the failure of
technology standards to meet business requirements, IDC said.
</P>
<P>
There is a danger that the Internet will not complete its
promise as a business infrastructure opening up new markets and
encouraging new ways of doing business, IDC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
