<HEADLINE> Europe Stops E. African Fish Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 16 (Xinhua)-- The European Union (EU) has
decided to ban importation of fish products from east Africa from
July 1, which is likely to cripple the region's booming fishing
industry.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's New Vision reported that the ban is to affect the
local fishing industry which has yet to come to terms with the
effects of last December's ban of fresh fish and frozen fish
import.
</P>
<P>
The ban is implemented due to worries over the alleged
contamination by cholera and other bio-chemical substances, it
added.
</P>
<P>
The EU has sent an official note to the countries that export
fish products to them. And Uganda has acknowledged that it has
received the note.
</P>
<P>
"Yes it is true we have received the letter. We have nothing
to comment on the issue," an official in charge of fisheries in
the ministry of agriculture was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Fish is a big foreign exchange earner for Uganda. It earned 75
million U.S. Dollars for the country in 1997. The EU is
traditionally the main export market for east Afirca's fish. It
has in the recent part put in strict regulations over the
processing of food for human consumption.
</P>
<P>
Previously, it put a ban on fish imports from Uganda because
of Ugandan factories and products not meeting the new EU
standards on food and a scare that Uganda had the intention to
spray chemicals on the Lake Victoria to fight the water hyacinth.
</P>
</TEXT>
