<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong Kong
Special Administration Region (SAR) welcomed Tuesday the
Australian government's agreement to sign with it a memorandum of
understanding (MOU) on information technology (IT) cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was announced by Australia's deputy prime
minister and minister for finance after their meeting with SAR
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa, who is currently on a visit to the
country.
</P>
<P>
An SAR government spokesman said Australia is advanced in IT
development and applications. "The signing of the MOU will enable
Hong Kong to benefit from the experience and expertise of
Australia."
</P>
<P>
"This will help us maintain our lead in IT and foster the
growth of Hong Kong's IT industry," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony for the MOU in Canberra next Monday,
Secretary for Information Technology and Broadcasting K. C. Kwong
will represent the SAR government while Australia will be
represented by its chief executive of the Office of Government
Information Technology.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong signed the first MOU of this nature with Canada here
last month. The SAR would continue to explore opportunities for
similar bilateral arrangements on IT cooperation with other
places, the spokesman added. 
</P>
