<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Airport to Cut Night Landing Fee by Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Macao International Airport
Company (CAM) announced Tuesday that from June 20 this year,
all landing charges at the airport between 11:00 p.m. and 7:00
a.m. will be cut by half.
</P>
<P>
The CAM said in a press release that the new charges, recently
approved by the Macao government, will apply to both scheduled and
non-scheduled operations of passenger and all-cargo airlines at
the airport, which is open 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
The night landing fee for a 395-ton Boeing 747, for instance,
will drop from 20,656 patacas (about 2,582 U.S. dollars) to 10,328
patacas (about 1,291 dollars) from the coming Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the airport will waive the passenger departure
charge for all air travelers who are to continue their journey
from the airport within 24 hours of arrival. That would mean a
saving of between 80 patacas (about 10 dollars) and 130 patacas
(about 16.25 dollars) per adult passenger, depending on their
destination.
</P>
<P>
The release said the moves are designed to stimulate additional
traffic at the airport, which has felt the pressure as the Hong
Kong new airport is to be inaugurated very soon.
</P>
<P>
The airport, which started operation in November 1995, has so
far handled more than 4 million passengers and over 90,000 tons of
 air cargo. Compared with the first four months of last year, the
passenger flow grew 14 percent and cargo flow, 40 percent in the
same period this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 14 regular airlines are now using the Macao airport,
which has weekly flights of 440 to 28 destinations worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
