<HEADLINE> Police Blame Government for Loopholes in Marseille Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- French police unions Tuesday blamed
the govenrment for leaving loopholes in measures to prevent
violence during the match between England and Tunisia in
Marseille on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Violent clashes took place from Sunday till Monday in Marseille
between English and Tunisian fans, during which 48 people were
injured and 50 arrested, most of them English fans.
</P>
<P>
Gerard Boyer, the secretary general of the Alliance police
union told Agence France Presse that among the 2,000 policemen
mobilized in the field to control the hooligans, only 600 are
specialized in maintaining public order, all the latter being the
elite CRS or gendarmery military police.
</P>
<P>
"There is a hesitation to intervene rapidly, when the primary
incidents took place, which was also the case" during the
incidents at Champs Elysee in Paris last Friday, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another national police union the SNPT said that the incidents
in Marseille were not inevitable or hazardous.
</P>
<P>
"The misbehavior and exactions of the hooligans being
sufficiently known beforehand, the preventive measures and
protection could have been made efficiently," it said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the national police were in the field to protect
persons and properties, instead of waging urban guerrilla
warfare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
