<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Will Bangladeshi PM Help Ease Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina left here for New Delhi Tuesday morning for a one-day visit
aimed at defusing the tension in South Asia in the aftermath of
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan last month.
</P>
<P>
This is the first trip of Hasina to India since the new Indian
government led by Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee from the
Bharatiya Janata Party came to power in March this year.
</P>
<P>
She is also scheduled to visit Pakistan on June 24 on a similar
one-day trip.
</P>
<P>
"This... visit is to discuss... bilateral issues" and would
fully concentrate on bilateral issues, Foreign Minister Abdus
Samad Azad said Monday, denying speculation that the prime
minister would play the role of a mediator between India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here, however, said the Bangladeshi prime
minister would certainly discuss with Vajpayee issues such as
nuclear non-proliferation and stability in South Asia during her
current visit and with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in a
visit later this month.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Hasina expressed the hope to visit New Delhi
and Islamabad "as soon as possible" to discuss with her Indian and
Pakistani counterparts the situation arising from the nuclear
explosions by India and Pakistan. This showed her desire to play a
part in easing the tension in the region, according to the
analysts.
</P>
<P>
In separate letters to Vajpayee and Sharif, Hasina said an arms
race involving nuclear weapons and missile technology would be
detrimental to development and cooperation and affect the
atmosphere of cooperation and friendship in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government has so far made no direct comments
on the nuclear tests by both India and Pakistan and has been
accused by opposition parties of being "weak" in dealing with such
an issue as nuclear tests which would seriously affect regional
stability.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh should conspicuously express its objection to the
tests, the opposition said, as they had caused serious concerns
among the public in the country.
</P>
<P>
Hasina's visit was also partially aimed at improving her image,
the analysts pointed out.
</P>
<P>
As Bangladesh is heavily dependent on India economically, any
deterioration of bilateral relations would be disastrous and the
implementation of the Ganges water sharing treaty and the
Chittagong Hill Tracts peace accord would become impossible
without India's cooperation, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Awami League government regards the 30-year water sharing
treaty the country signed with India in December 1996 and the
peace treaty the government concluded with the hill tribals in
December last year as two of its major achievements.
</P>
<P>
That was why the Bangladeshi prime minister said in her letters
to Vajpayee and Sharif that "every country will decide its own
security perceptions and take measures accordingly," they said.
</P>
<P>
And on the nuclear tests, the most direct comment of Hasina was
that "nuclear weapons did not enhance a country's security in the
post-Cold War (era) and indeed, could diminish it." She apparently
tried to avoid annoying either of Bangladesh's two neighbors, the
analysts noted.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the prime minister had to focus on
bilateral issues during her visits to India and Pakistan, with an
eye to gaining political support at home, they added.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Dhaka said on Monday, "We
(the United States) hope her efforts will contribute to lessening
of tension in the region." German and Japanese envoys also
expressed similar hopes.
</P>
<P>
But the analysts doubted whether the Bangladeshi prime minister
could really play a role in mediating between India and Pakistan
and thus help ease the tension in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's First Wine, Spirits Expo Held in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- V&AMP;S, the first international
wine and spirits exhibition for the Asia-Pacific region, opened
Tuesday in Hong Kong, one of Asia's leading import and re-export
centers for wine and spirits.
</P>
<P>
More than 700 direct and indirect exhibitors from 31 countries
displayed their products at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center, with half of the exhibition area taken by
France.
</P>
<P>
Consumption of spirits and wine has grown steadily in the
region over the past decade, acting Hong Kong Chief Executive
Donald Tsang told the opening ceremony of the expo which will last
until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Asian spirits market grew about 44 percent by value while
the wine market increased by about 14 percent from 1992 to 1996,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"In Hong Kong we have no doubt helped that trend along by
reducing duties on alcoholic beverages," Tsang said, whose 1997
budget put in place a one-third reduction in wine duty.
</P>
<P>
The event was organized by VINEXPO, an international wine and
spirits expo staged in France biannually. The promising figures in
Asia prompted VINEXPO to create a specific exhibition for the
region, said Robert Beynat, chief executive of VINEXPO and V&AMP;S.
</P>
<P>
An attendance of 6,000 professionals from the region is
expected, including importers, wholesalers, commercial agents and
retail chain buyers.
</P>
<P>
To help trade visitors increase their knowledge of products and
discover the many facets of the continually developing sector, a
"university" program will be presented during the expo featuring
about 50 lectures and tastings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
