<HEADLINE> Malaysia, New Zealand Sign Open Skies Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and New Zealand
signed Tuesday an "open skies" agreement to allow their airlines
to operate between and beyond the two countries without
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here by Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim and his New Zealand counterpart, Winston
Peters.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik said in a statement
in conjunction with the agreement that it will facilitate the
future development of trade, investment, tourism and
people-to-people contacts between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"The 'open skies' will also afford various opportunities for
the designated airlines of Malaysia and New Zealand to develop and
enhance their air services and also to effect cooperative
agreements and smart partnership," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ling said that although aviation ties between the two countries
started only eight years ago in 1989, he is pleased that both
countries have adopted a liberal and positive approach to the
development of such links.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, New Zealand Transport Minister Maurice Williamson
said efficient international air transport links are vital to his
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"The new air service agreement is consistent with this
objective and a signal of our commitment to liberalizing trade and
investment," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the accord offers significant opportunities for
airlines to provide efficient and competitive services to benefit
the business communities and wider traveling public from both
countries.
</P>
<P>
Peters, who arrived here Monday night for a four-day visit,
called on Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohammad and his
deputy Anwar here Tuesday and had an hour-long discussion with
Mahathir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
