<HEADLINE> Share Prices Further Slide in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices futher slide in Tokyo
Tuesday as the U.S. dollar's surge to the upper 146 yen level gave
investors reason to sell shares.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 104.79 points, or 0.71
percent, from Monday's close to end at 14,720.38.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 10.74 points or 0.92 percent to
1,156.47.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 430 million
shares from Monday's 313 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan was the day's most heavily traded
issue.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo stock market opened lower on the more than 200 point
decline of the Dow Jones Industrial Average overnight on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Negativity in the market was further fueled by the dollar's surge
to a high of 146.75 yen, traders said.
</P>
<P>
However, sentiment gradually improved to send stock prices into the
positive column after the Japanese currency rebounded by more than 4
yen against the dollar around noon to a high of 142.40 yen.
</P>
<P>
But Slight gains generated by the yen's rebound were wiped out by
late selling from foreign investors on lingering concerns over Japan's
economy and the yen's declining to the 145 level against the dollar,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,336 issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 756 to 334, with 177 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
