<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Efforts to Curb Devaluation of Japanese Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government today
expressed concern over the downward Japanese yen in the foreign
exchange market and urged relevant countries, Japan in particular,
to take effective measures to curb the further devaluation of its
currency.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Bangzao, spokesman for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign
Affairs, made the remarks today in the routine press briefing.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, the fall of the yen in the monetary market
triggered a new round of unrest in the financial market in
Southeast Asia. Taking into consideration the impact of the
Japanese economy and Japanese yen on the economies of East and
Southeast Asia, "the further devaluation of yen is detrimental to
the recovery of the regional financial market and the economic
adjustment in the region," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He urged relevant countries, especially Japan, to face up with
the reality with "courage and wisdom," and enhance cooperation in
stabilizing the yen so as to create favorable conditions for the
regional economic recovery. "The move is also in the interest of
Japan," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the rumor of the devaluation of Chinese renminbi, Zhu said
that China has made great contributions and paid a price in
stabilizing the Asian financial turmoil. "The rumor is totally
groundless," he said, adding that the stance of the Chinese
leaders and the People's Bank of China over the issue is
"consistent and firm."
</P>
<P>
"The international balance of payments in China is in good
shape and renminbi will remain stable," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
