</P>
<P>
In the meeting, which Tung's spokeswoman described as "quite
friendly," they also discussed extending electronic travel
authority (electronic visas) by Australia to HKSAR passport
holders, a spokeswoman for the chief executive told Xinhua in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
Tung said extending electronic visas to HKSAR passport holders
would facilitate exchange between Australia and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Tung also met Australian Deputy Prime Minister
Tim Fischer and Treasurer Peter Costello and Premier of Victoria
State Jeff Kennett.
</P>
<P>
Fischer expressed his interest in Hong Kong's infrastructure
development, saying he is looking forward to seeing the opening of
Hong Kong's new airport, which Australians were involved in the
construction process.
</P>
<P>
Tung told Fischer that Hong Kong welcomes talented people in
its development in the future, referring to the 30,000 Australians
working in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We have a level playing field for everyone from every
country," the chief executive said.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Premier Kennett, Tung was briefed on
the development and application of information technology (IT) in
Victoria, the leading business and manufacturing center in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Tung said the state's experience in IT gave him an insight into
how to develop IT in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive also paid particular attention to the
state's electronic delivery of government services to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
Early Tuesday, the chief executive made a keynote speech at the
Australia Summit held in Melbourne, capital of Victoria State,
focusing on the successful implementation of the "One Country, Two
Systems" concept in Hong Kong, how Hong Kong's has been affected
by the Asian financial turmoil and how Hong Kong is coping with
it.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said Australia and Hong Kong also initialed a
memorandum of understanding on information technology, which is to
be signed officially on June 26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
