<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Scientists Link Constipation to Colon Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 15 (Xinhua) -- American scientists found that
people who frequently felt constipated were more associated with colon
cancer than those who did not complain of constipation, according to a
report in the July issue of the journal Epidemiology.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Eric J. Jacobs from Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center and
Dr. Emily White from the University of Washington, both in Seattle,
studied 424 men and women with colon cancer and 414 people without the
disease, and found that the former were more than four times as likely
to develop colon cancer as the latter.
</P>
<P>
They speculate that constipation may increase the risk of colon
cancer because "the longer transit time associated with constipation
may result in greater colonic absorption of water and fiber
metabolites, leading to lower-weight, harder stools with higher
concentrations of carcinogens."
</P>
<P>
They recommended a way of preventing common forms of constipation:
adoption of a higher-vegetable, low-red meat diet and a regular
exercise regimen.
</P>
<P>
"Such a lifestyle may reduce the risk of colon cancer as well as
the risk of several other chronic diseases," they wrote in the journal
Epidemiology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
