<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey has planned to invest 30 billion U.S. dollars
in the infrastructure in the next 10 years, a report in the Daily
News said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The infrastructural projects, mainly in transportation and
energy sectors, include a third bridge over the Bosphorus Straits,
a causeway over the Izmir Gulf, state railways linking the capital
Ankara and Istanbul, the country's largest city.
</P>
<P>
An oil pipeline from Baku, capital of Azerbaijan, to southern
Turkish city of Ceyhan will be the largest project in the field of
energy in the next few years. The segment of the pipeline in
Turkey will cost about 2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turkey will also spend another 2.5 billion dollars to build a
nuclear power plant in the next years. After being completed, the
power plant can generate an annual 10 billion kilowatt-hours of
electricity.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Airlines will buy two A-340-300 Airbus jets worth 700
million dollars in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Due to difficult economic situations and overpricing
of the properties, Lebanese real estate developers are facing a
stagnant market, the Daily Star newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A report released by the Lebanese government said that property
transactions in 1997 stood at a lower level than in 1996 with
47,373 properties sold for 2.25 billion U.S. dollars compared with
48,141 properties sold in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report said that more than 250,000 apartments and office
blocks remain vacant.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 3,310 properties in the capital, where nearly a third
of the country's population live, were sold for 565.3 million
dollars, representing 25.11 percent of the total real estate value
and 6.99 percent of the volumes of sale in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- The Kuwaiti petroleum foundation is expected to make
a profit of 670 million dinars (2.19 billion U.S. dollars), the
Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the Financial and Economic Committee of
the Kuwaiti National Assembly said the expenditures of the
state-owned foundation are estimated at 3.26 billion dinars (10.64
billion dollars) and the revenues at 3.93 billion dinars (12.83
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The World Gold Council has called on the central
banks of the Gulf Arab countries to increase gold reserves to help
shore up the prices of gold in the world markets, the Alam Al Yom
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The central banks have been asked to augment their reserves to
at least 10 to 15 percent to the total financial reserves from the
current 2 to 3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
