<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Stresses Need to Avoid Military Action in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 16 (Xinhua) -- During a telephone conversation on
Monday with U.S. President Bill Clinton, Russian President Boris
Yeltsin stressed the need to avoid military action in Kosovo, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the phone call made one day before meeting with his Yugoslav
counterpart Slobodan Milosevic, Yeltsin expressed pleasure with
the statement issued by the foreign ministers of the Group of
Eight industrial countries in London.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said in the statement that the G-8 supported
Russia's efforts in seeking a peaceful settlement of the conflict,
including the upcoming talks between Russian and Yugoslav
presidents.
</P>
<P>
During the telephone call, Yeltsin once again voiced Russia's
opposition to using force in Kosovo and called for a negotiated
settlement for the region, Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, on his part, expressed the hope that the talks between
Yeltsin and Milosevic, who arrived in Moscow Monday evening for a
one-day visit, will be a success and lay the foundation for a
speedy settlement of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Russian and U.S. presidents shared the view that an early
start of talks between Belgrade and Kosovo Albanians will
facilitate peace in the Balkans, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
In the conversation, special attention was also paid to
Russia's ratification of the START II nuclear disarmament treaty.
Both presidents confirmed their adherence to speeding up the
ratification process, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Russia's State Duma (the lower house)
declared that it will postpone consideration of START II until
autumn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
