<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Supports Suit Against Tobacco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Health Minister Yehoshua
Matza has expressed his support for a health insurance
organization in its initiative on filing a suit against a tobacco
company, the Jerusalem Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Monday by the Health Ministry, Matza
"congratulated" Maccabi Health Insurance Scheme on the suit of
1.75 billion shekels (about 480 million U.S. dollars) it filed
earlier in the day in the Tel Aviv District Court against the
Dubek tobacco company.
</P>
<P>
Following a worldwide trend that began with successful action
against a number of U.S. and European cigarette manufacturers,
Maccabi is arguing that the defendant is responsible for damages
connected to its expenditures on smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
Maccabi is demanding 250 million shekels (about 68.6 million
dollars) from Dubek for each year since 1991, the last year before
a law limiting tobacco selling was publicized.
</P>
<P>
The suit is separate from the other filed last fall by dozens
of former smokers, or families of deceased smokers. The plaintiffs
claimed that they were not aware of nicotine being "added to make
cigarettes more addictive and the health dangers posed by smoking,
which were not mentioned for decades in Dubek's advertising."
</P>
<P>
Ran Rahav, spokesman for the government-recognized monopoly
that sells most of the cigarettes smoked by Israelis, said Dubek
"had not yet received" the documents concerning Maccabi's
suit. "When we receive them, we will comment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Another health fund, Kupat Holim Clalit, is now seriously
considering the possibility of joining the suit, according to the
newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mangrove Forest: Wonderful View in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Tourists, who travel in south
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, will be fascinated by a
wonderful view of thick submarine forest -- mangrove.
</P>
<P>
A particular kind of tropical and semitropical plant, the
mangrove benefits the coastal residents. It roots deeply in
the seabed to fix the sands, and stretches its luxuriant branches
and leaves on the surface of the water, building a seawall to
resist attacking tides.
</P>
<P>
The mangrove is good for the ocean's ecosystem. Its leaves and
flowers serve as food for fish, its roots are homes for crabs and
eels, and shellfishes are often found to stay on its trunks.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has 5,654 hectares of mangrove forests, the country's
largest, accounting for one-third of the nation's total. Since the
1990s, the region has invested more than six million yuan to
establish two mangrove forest natural reserves, and plant about
3,440 hectares of such trees.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, the state approved to set up the Shankou Mangrove
Forest Natural Reserve, where mangrove trees are under good
protection and have become a tourism attraction as well a place
for scientific research.
</P>
<P>
The province's marine management department has established
cooperative contacts with a research institute of the United
States, and exchanged investigation groups with Malaysia,
Hongkong over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The unusual beautiful scenery of mangrove forests can also be
seen in Guangdong, Hainan, Taiwan and Fujian provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
