<HEADLINE> Turkey to Invest 30 Billion Dollars in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has planned to invest 30
billion U.S. dollars in the infrastructure in the next 10 years, a
report in the Daily News said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The infrastructural projects, mainly in transportation and
energy sectors, are aimed at giving a strong impetus to Turkey's
economic development in the 21st century, experts were quoted by
the English-language newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some transportation projects, including a third bridge over the
Bosphorus Straits, a causeway over the Izmir Gulf, state railways
linking the capital Ankara and Istanbul, the country's largest
city, will obtain financial assistance from domestic and overseas
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Companies from Japan, Italy, Britain, France and Germany have
reportedly shown great interest in the construction of the third
Bosphorus bridge, which is estimated to cost 1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Turkish Airlines will buy two A-340-300 Airbus
jets worth 700 million dollars in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
An oil pipeline from Baku, capital of Azerbaijan, to southern
Turkish city of Ceyhan will be the largest project in the field of
energy in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The segment of the pipeline in Turkey will cost about 2 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turkey will also spend another 2.5 billion dollars to build a
nuclear power plant in the next years. After being completed, the
power plant can generate an annual 10 billion kilowatt-hours of
electricity. 
</P>
