<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Real Estate Developers Facing Flat Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Due to the difficult economic
situation and overpricing of the properties in Lebanon, Lebanese
real estate developers are facing a stagnant market, the Daily
Star newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a report released for 1997 by the Lebanese
government as saying that property transactions in 1997 changed
little in comparison with 1996 with 47,373 properties sold
in Lebanon for 2.25 billion U.S. dollars against 48,141
properties in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that more than 250,000 apartments and office
blocks in Lebanon remain vacant.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 3,310 properties in the capital of Beirut where
nearly a third of the country's population live were sold for
565.3 million dollars, representing 25.11 percent of the total
real estate value and 6.99 percent of the volumes of sale in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the average price of an apartment in Beirut
stood at 171,000 dollars against 47,000 dollars outside the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Michal Morkos, a statistician who helped prepare the report,
said that the demand for new apartments in Beirut since 1995 had
dropped by 20 to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
"But we can't really say that we've reached a serious state
because the Lebanese sooner or later will buy properties to
settle down with their families," Morkos said.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the slowdown in the property market it was
still performing more successfully than other sectors of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
"We must admit that although there was no significant rise in
property sales over the last three years, the Lebanese still view
lands and apartments as solid investments," Morkos added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Lebanese expatriates represented around 40
percent of property buyers in 1996-97. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
