<HEADLINE> Estrada Welcomes Deferment of Oil Price Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President-Elect Joseph
Estrada Tuesday welcomed the deferment of an oil price increase
which would affect three socially-sensitive petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
The deferment was announced by the Energy Regulatory Board
after Estrada appealed to it to shelve the price rise, saying the
masses would bear a heavy burden if the prices of liquefied
petroleum gas, kerosene and regular gas were raised.
</P>
<P>
Estrada expressed apprehension that the country might be in
tough times had the hike been imposed, citing the effects of the
currency turmoil hitting the country and the ongoing recession in
Japan which could hurt the entire region.
</P>
<P>
The recession in Japan caused a significant drop in the value
of the yen, dragging the peso to a four-month low of 42.58 a U.S.
dollar Monday.
</P>
<P>
To prevent future increases in the cost of oil, Estrada
reiterated that he would ask the congress to review the
implementation of the oil deregulation law when he assumes office
on June 30.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for the congress to give the government
enough time to adopt measures encouraging new players into the oil
industry to create the competition needed to stabilize the prices.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
