<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Sees Fewer Landmine Casualties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has seen much fewer
casualties of landmine and other explosives since the launching
of the prevention program against landmines and other explosives
started in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Baltazar Ussaca, director of the program, made the remark
during his recent tour to Vilankulo, a southern Mozambique city.
</P>
<P>
While there were a reported 127 cases of the landmine and
other explosive casualties in 1996, there were only 61 reported
cases 1997, reducing the casualty rate from one case in every two
and half days to one in five days. No such case has been reported
this year.
</P>
<P>
The country set up a national commission for landmine
clearance under the help of international organization after it
won independence in 1992, and set up a national co-ordination
program against landmines and other explosives.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about one to two million landmines were
deployed during the 16 years of civil war in the country, with
only 60,000 of them cleared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
