<HEADLINE> Sichuan Increases Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Sichuan Province in southwest
China has recently decided to increase its investment for 1998 by
10 billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars) to 118 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The adjustment is aimed to boost domestic demand and expand
consumption, so as to ensure the fulfilment of a nine percent
growth of the province's gross domestic products (GDP) in 1998,
according to vice governor Zou Guangyan.
</P>
<P>
The increased investment will be injected in the sectors of
water conservancy, transportation, telecommunication, urban
construction and housing.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of last year's "low inflation and high growth",
the GDP of the province grew by eight percent in the first four
months of this year, a 2.2 percentage points lower than the growth
rate in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the retail of consumption goods grew by only 6.7
percent, as compared with 13.1 percent in the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the Asian financial crisis, Sichuan accomplished
exports of 480 million US dollars in the first four months of this
year, up 1.5 percent. However, the growth rate was 4.3 percentage
points lower than last year's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
