<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Forex Inflows Still Weak, Says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Foreign exchange inflows into the
Bank of Zambia continues to remain weak and the banking system's
transactions totaled only 392 million U.S. Dollars in the last
four months.
</P>
<P>
The latest Citibank treasury letter issued here states that
the central bank recorded no foreign exchange inflows in the
first two weeks of May while total payments, on the other hand,
for the same period amounted to 8.5 million Dollars, Times of
Zambia reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The total foreign exchange transacted through the banking
system during the four months to April totaled 392 million
Dollars compared to the 469 million Dollars during the same
period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This represented a drop of 77 million Dollars or 16 percent
showing a further decline in foreign exchange supply to the
market this year.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the tightness in the supply of foreign exchange
in relation to demand, the Zambian Kwacha has remained under
pressure. In May, the Kwacha depreciated by approximately five
percent in the inter-bank.
</P>
<P>
On a year date basis, the Kwacha has depreciated by 33 percent
in the formal market but it is expected that the rate of
depreciation will decline following the success of the Paris Club
meeting held early last month at which Zambia managed to get
530-million Dollars pledged aid, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In June, it is projected that the Kwacha will depreciate by
between 2.5 to three percent with the outright rate projected at
1930 to a Dollar by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) copper
production, which used to generate over 90 percent of the
country's foreign exchange, dropped by six percent to 17,780
tonnes for April and 11 percent below the March level partly due
to non-availability of supplies into the production process.
</P>
<P>
This will translate into lower foreign exchange inflows thus
exerting pressure on the already fragile foreign exchange supply,
said the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
