<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rising Incomes for Rural Tibetans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Yuqiong, a native of Mainling
County, Nyingchi Prefecture, in the Tibet Autonomous Region, has
accumulated fixed asset of over 200,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Her family of six owns a house, truck and various pieces of
property. Yuqiong recounted that she never dreamed of buying a
truck before the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Many Tibetan families have become prosperous thanks to local
government policies designed to increase the prosperity of local
farmers and herdsmen.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that per capita income of local farmers
and herdsmen has reached 1,040 yuan a year, up some 50 percent on
figures for the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also reveal that each 100 Tibetan household shares
nine automobiles and six tractors. Over 90 percent of Tibetan
farmers and herdsmen have constructed new houses in the past two
decades and per capita floor space in the region's rural areas has
reached 20 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The region has pledged to shake off poverty by the end of this
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
