<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former State Head Released in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State, General
Abdulsalam Abubakar Tuesday ordered the immediate release of nine
political detainees, including former Head of State, General
Olusegun Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued in Abuja by David Attah, the Chief Press
Secretary to the head of state, said the move is to "facilitate
the process of national reconciliation, reconstruction and
successful completion of the social-political transition
program."
</P>
<P>
Abubakar in the statement urged the released persons to
co-operate with the government in the efforts at nation building.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to the international community to appreciate
the efforts at solving the country's problems by showing greater
understanding and sensitivity in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
General Obasanjo, the head of Nigeria's military government
from 1976 to 1979, was arrested on March 13, 1995 for alleged
involvement in a failed coup against the military government of
General Sani Abacha, who died a sudden death last Monday.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo is now serving a 15-year jail term in a prison in
Yola, capital Adamawa State in eastern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Other persons released Tuesday include Alhaji Dasuki, the
Sultan of Sokoto; Chief Bola Ige, former governor of Oyo State;
Chief Frank Kokori, former Secretary-General of the National
Union of Petroleum and Natural Gas Workers; Chief Milton Dabbi,
former president of the Petroleum and Natural Gas Senior Staff
Association; Chris Anyanwu, publisher of a weekly magazine.
</P>
<P>
Others are Beko Ransome-Kuti, chairman of the Committee for
the Defense of Human Rights; Chief Olabiyi Durojaiye, a chieftain
of the National Democratic Coalition; Uwen Udoh.
</P>
<P>
Also Tuesday, the Lagos State government ordered the release
of 18 persons arrested last Friday at an illegal mass rally.
Among them is Chief Gani Fawehinmi, a lawyer and leader of the
opposition group, the Joint Action Committee of Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
