<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Copper Mines Needs Urgent Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Consolidated Cooper Mines
(ZCCM) faces a very bleak future without an urgent injection of
investment and various experts have called for a quick decision
to salvage the mines and avoid serious economic repercussions,
according to Financial Mail.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper reported that during the monthly meeting
of the Economic Association of Zambia the experts scoffed at the
country's negotiating team for ZCCM privatization for attaching
too much importance to the price consideration instead of seeking
a future investment.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Zambia Association of Chambers of Commerce and
Industry Chairman of the Committee on Mines, Theo Bull, as saying
recently that there is too much focus on the price instead of
looking at it from the immediate need of investment.
</P>
<P>
Selani Mwenachenya, a mining expert, also said the fundamental
problem of ZCCM is not cash but rather re-investments.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia faces a problem because it is not negotiating
from a point of strength.
</P>
<P>
He said that right now "we are at greater risk given that ZCCM
is running and the mines cannot be covered or closed."
</P>
<P>
Mwenachenya said ZCCM might not exist much longer unless
something is done to make it viable.
</P>
<P>
Recently negotiations on the sale of some ZCCM assets between
Zambia and some big international mining companies broke due to
disagreement over the prices of the assets.
</P>
<P>
The breakdown has delayed the privatization process of ZCCM,
the biggest foreign exchange earner of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
