<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Rebounds in May (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
M1, or circulating capital and deposits in banks and companies,
dropped by 15.5 percent on an annual basis by the end of May, with
growth in M2 represented by a 10.8 percent rise in currency in
circulation and 10.1 percent rise in current deposits.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade volume for May reached 26.22 billion
U.S. dollars, down 2.5 percent on the 1997 period. The export
volume of 14.93 billion dollars represented a 1.5 percent decline
on the figure for the previous year. The decline also brought an
end to 22 consecutive months of rising exports. The import volume
fell by 3.8 percent to 11.29 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report showed a 1.5 percent decline in retail prices
and 1.4 percent fall in consumer prices, with the drops
underscoring the emergence of deflation resulting from sluggish
markets and low efficiency of the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
SSB officials noted that the May index for macroeconomic
operations indicated a rebound in economic growth resulting from
effective central government's policies which stimulated domestic
demand. Despite the fact that the growth rate was far from
equalling past records, it nonetheless signaled the excellent
potential for achieving sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
"However, healthy economic growth must rely on quality and
steady growth in the domestic market, rather than on increased
quantity," according to SSB sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
