<HEADLINE> Microsoft Expands Support Staff for Windows 98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft company has added
more than 1,000 technicians to its support team to help solve
potential problems that may occur after its Windows 98 software is
released on June 25.
</P>
<P>
The addition is a 40 percent increase to the technical support
team, which provides after-sale services including answering
technical questions and tracking customers' feedback and their
product suggestions, said the company on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Windows 98 has new tools that help customers diagnose and fix
problems themselves without support calls," said Lori Moore,
general manager for Microsoft technical support unit. "However, we
want to ensure that they will still be able to receive the same
support they have grown accustomed to receiving from Microsoft."
</P>
<P>
Microsoft is the world's largest software maker and its Windows
software is used on 80 percent of the world's desktop computers.
</P>
</TEXT>
