<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Press Highly Cover English Football Hooligans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- All French newspapers carried
front-page pictures of English football fans clashing with
Tunisian fans and French police in Marseille on Monday, when the
English football team was playing Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Most papers did not hide their dislike of the English fans and
their disgust of the hooligans who they said had not only tarred
the football sport, but also shown disrespect to France.
</P>
<P>
The daily Echo Republicain said that one wants to say: How good
it would be that England be eliminated! But the paper said that
the French should not go too far in their anger because the
British government has given "carte blanch" to France to act
against the hooligans.
</P>
<P>
The daily France Soir said in its front-page story accompanied
with a big photo of English hooligans:"It's all predictable."
</P>
<P>
It accused the English of "transforming Marseille into a battle
field and dragging into their wake the youths of the Northern
district of the city" where live a large North African community.
</P>
<P>
The Communist daily Humanity used two whole pages to report
Monday's event in Marseille. Under the headline "Warm Beer and
Blood in the Cup," the daily said that some English fans shouted
racist slogans and gave Nazi salute during their rampage.
</P>
<P>
The daily Liberation published a picture showing a beer
drinking skinhead English hooligan burning a Tunisian national
flag in the old port district of Marseille.
</P>
<P>
"A band of little Nazis drunken with beer should be corrected,
as well as the French followers of the National Front," said the
paper.
</P>
<P>
It also accused the organizers of only wanting to make money
and allowing all kinds of hooligans come to watch the match on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The daily Marseillaise said that since the tragedy of Heysel in
Belgium, one has understood that suppression of individuals is not
enough to eliminate the phenomenon of football hooliganism, which
was born in England during the rule of Prime Ministre Marguerite
Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
It said that England in the "black years" under Thatcher is
marked by an explosion of unemployment, destruction of social
welfare in Britain and exclusion of the poor in great scale.
</P>
<P>
"The dramatic weekend tells us: the football and the World Cup
are not isolated islands of the crisis of our society," it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
