<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Bank Not to Intervene in Peso Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
would not intervene in the fresh round of depreciation that the
peso is facing due to the sharp fall of the Japanese yen, a senior
bank official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Reyes, deputy governor of the central bank, said the
bank would allow the peso to seek its own level and let the market
forces decide the current market situation.
</P>
<P>
In case the currency situation worsens, what the central bank
will do is only to moderate the impacts of the peso depreciation,
he said, adding that the central bank would not use some of its
dollar reserves to replenish the foreign exchange shortage in the
market.
</P>
<P>
What the central bank is doing right now is just to wait and
see, especially when the prevailing economic recession is going on
in Japan, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Amid fears that the fall of the yen would spur another round of
financial crisis, the peso fell by 5.5 percent to 42.58 a dollar
on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
