<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Progress in Sino-U.S. Military Exchanges (1) (by Correspondent Zhang Rongdian) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese People's Liberation
Army (PLA) will accept the invitation of the U.S. Army and will
for the first time send representatives to observe two
multinational military exercises scheduled for this summer.
</P>
<P>
The plan that the PLA will observe two exercises -- "Rim Pac"
Naval Exercises in the east Pacific, and "Cope Thunder" Air Force
Exercises in Alaska -- constitutes a major segment of the
"substantial progress" in the Sino-U.S. military exchanges and
cooperation over the past few years, according to a PLA official.
</P>
<P>
Such progress has resulted from frequent exchange of visits
by high-level officers from the two armies. The visits have helped
open channels for dialog related to relationships between the two
nations and two armies, as well as on global and regional security
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources report that Zhang Wannian, vice-Chairman of
China's Central Military Commission (CMC), will pay an
official visit to the United States in the near future.
</P>
<P>
In the past year and more, CMC Vice-Chairman and Defense
Minister Chi Haotian, Chief of PLA General Staff Fu Quanyou, and a
number of other senior PLA officers have visited the U.S. A number
of senior U.S. military officers have paid return visits to China,
including U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen and General John
Shalikashivili, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
During last October's historic U.S. visit, Chinese President
Jiang Zemin and President Bill Clinton reached a consensus on
building a constructive Sino-U.S. strategic partnership geared to
the 21st century and on expanding exchanges between the two armed
forces. The visit provided a precious opportunity for the
development of bilateral military ties.
</P>
<P>
The consensus reached between the two leaders resulted in last
December's establishment of a regular vice ministerial level
defense consulting system between defense departments in the two
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Progress in Sino-U.S. Military Exchanges (2) (by Correspondent Zhang Rongdian) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cohen visited China last January and the two sides signed an
agreement on establishing a consultation mechanism for
strengthening maritime military safety, and avoiding accidents,
misunderstandings and wrongful judgements between the naval and
air forces of the two countries. The first annual meeting on
implementation of the agreement will be held in Beijing next month.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two sides conducted fruitful exchanges in many
professional areas, including military training and logistics, as
well as military law and science.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also reached an agreement on matters
concerning U.S. military vessels and aircraft visiting Hong Kong
following China's resumption of sovereignty over the region on
July 1, 1997. Some 50 U.S. warships belonging to 36 naval groups
and 65 sorties of military aircraft manned by 25,500 servicemen
have since visited Hong Kong for either logistical supply missions
or rest and recuperation visits. The two sides also agreed to
exchange information on matters related to humanitarian assistance
and disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
Friendly exchanges between the armed forces of China and the
United States fully demonstrate that both sides attach great
importance to the development of bilateral military relations, and
signify that related relations are an important part of
Sino-U.S. ties.
</P>
<P>
The increase in bilateral military exchanges has not only
contributed greatly to the development of overall
Sino-U.S. relations, but also to the maintenance of peace and
stability in the Asia-Pacific Region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Observers in Beijing believe the upcoming state visit to China
by President Clinton will greatly enhance mutual understanding and
trust, while at the same time adding vigor to the development of
bilateral relations and cementing friendly contacts between their
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
However, such exchanges and cooperation do not mean that China
and the U.S. will form a military alliance. China believes that
under the new historical condition, the only practical way to
ensure peace and security is to conduct dialog and cooperation to
increase mutual understanding and trust.
</P>
<P>
The most sensitive and key problem remaining in
Sino-U.S. relations centers on the Taiwan issue, according to an
unnamed official from the Foreign Affairs Office under China's
National Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that proper handling of the Taiwan issue in line
with the principles in the three joint Sino-U.S. communiques will
lead to the healthy and smooth development of relations between the
two countries and their armed forces.
</P>
<P>
China is fully prepared to work with the United States to
maintain the momentum of growth in Sino-U.S. military ties featuring
"more stable, pragmatic and active" attitudes in terms of
exchanges and cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
