<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Rebounds in May (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Hope for a rebound in the Chinese
economy was finally realized in May this year, with most indices
for the national economy showing positive changes after several
months of sluggish performance, according to a report
released today by State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
China's industrial sectors achieved a May value-added of 168.1
billion yuan, up eight percent on the 1997 period, with the
year-on-year margin of increase rising 0.8 percentage points on
the April level.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report showed that the state-owned sector contributed
76 billion yuan to the industrial added value, a rise of 2.5
percent on an annual basis, while the collective sector generated
43.6 billion yuan, up 7.6 percent. The added value for
stockholding (corporations) companies, foreign-funded firms and
other economic sectors rose by 10.8 percent to 48.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The industrial value-added for the first five months of the
year grew by 7.9 percent on the previous year's period to end at
776.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's state-owned sector invested 400.6 billion yuan in fixed
assets, up 12.7 percent on an annual basis, with the year-on-year
margin growing by 0.5 percentage points on the January-April
period and by 2.4 percentage points on the overall average for the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the domestic market failed to see any hopeful
signs of a revival, with the country's May retail sales standing
at 226.5 billion yuan, up 6.8 percent the 1997 period. Rural areas
contributed 86.5 billion yuan to total retail sales, up 5.8
percent, with cities generating 140 billion yuan, up 7.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Deposits in China's financial institutions grew by
172.1 billion yuan in May, or 97.8 billion yuan growth on the
figure for the 1997 period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
