<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lhasa Reels Under High Temperatures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Lhasa, capital of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, has reeled under unseasonably high temperatures
for several consecutive days, with a record of 29.9 degrees
Centigrade reported on June 15.
</P>
<P>
The regional meteorological bureau attributed the high
temperatures to the impact of El Nino which has blocked the normal
arrival of the rainy season which usually begins in Lhasa at the
end of May.
</P>
<P>
While the highest daily temperature for last June hit 25
degrees C., the city has recorded 22 consecutive days of
temperatures above 25 degrees C. since May 19 this year.
</P>
<P>
The bureau noted that high temperatures which are expected to
continue for at least a few more days will not only harm the
growth of corps and grass, but will also threaten the health and
well-being of local residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Survey: American Men Neglect Health More Than Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A new survey released Monday
said that American men are more likely to neglect their health
than women.
</P>
<P>
The telephone survey of 1,017 adults, conducted by Opinion
Research International Corporation between April 23-26, found that
just 60 percent of American men have had the basic health check
more than one time within the last 12 months, compared with 76
percent of women.
</P>
<P>
While 60 percent of men said they are concerned about their
risk for prostate cancer, but just 35 percent said they had ever
been tested for that disease. Only 48 percent of men aged 55 to 64
had undergone a prostate exam, even though risks for prostate
cancer, the number two cancer among American men, rises with
increasing age.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, 57 percent of American women aged 45 to 54 said
they had been examined for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
"We have a large number of men who haven't even had a basic
health check since the Reagan administration," said Mike Lafavore,
editor-in-chief of Men's Health magazine, one of the co-sponsors
of the survey.
</P>
<P>
The results of the survey show that nearly 7 million men have
gone without a medical check-up for over 10 years, and more than
14 million men have not had a check-up in the past 5 years.
</P>
<P>
Younger men seemed to have a more laissez-faire attitude
towards their health compared with older men.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that just 62 percent of American men aged 18
to 34 said they recognized the value of a healthy diet, compared
with 71 percent of men aged 35 to 50, and 85 percent of men over
age 50. Younger men are also much more likely to smoke or skip
medical check-ups than their older brothers.
</P>
<P>
The survey cited the gap of attitudes towards personal health
as one of the reasons.
</P>
<P>
Just 26 of American men believe "health and fitness is the one
aspect of their life they would like to personally improve,"
according to the survey, compared with 36 percent of American
women. Similarly, only 50 percent of American men said they
recognized the importance of regular medical check-ups, compared
with 68 percent of American women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature: Chinese Views of United States (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
His company was the first Sino-foreign automotive joint venture
and the Cherokee jeeps it produces are one of the favorites of
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey showed that three quarters of Chinese
respondents knew of President Clinton's upcoming visit to China,
and 85 percent thought the visit would be a "positive step in
fostering bilateral relations".
</P>
<P>
The survey, which sampled 1,000 residents in Beijing, Shanghai,
Xi'an and six other cities between May 28-31, was conducted by the
Mainland Marketing Research Co, under the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
A number of people in their 50s and 60s retain deep impressions
of the former Soviet Union, while their children exhibit greater
interest in seeking information about the United States.
</P>
<P>
"My mother and father say the gap between the States and China
will be quite difficult to be bridged, but I think that different
social systems should learn from each other as long as the process
benefits their development," said Liu Hongwei, a student from
Beijing University, a prestigious institution of higher learning
which recently celebrated its centennial.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of people interviewed agreed that it is
important for China and the United States, two world powers, to
maintain and strengthen friendly cooperative relations which will
"be vital to world peace and stability".
</P>
<P>
A study by Yang Shengyu, an expert on American studies, noted
that the two countries have enjoyed good or comparatively good
relations during three-fourths of the time since the two countries
started contacts some 214 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Xiong Zhiyong, a professor at the Foreign Affairs Institute, said
the fact that China and the United States share many common
interests in terms of strategic importance has established an
important foundation for establishing a partnership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
