<HEADLINE> Turkey to Train Egyptian Technicians on F-16 Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has agreed to help train
Egyptian technicians on Turkish-made F-16 fighter planes in an
effort to enhance their defense cooperation, the Daily News
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language newspaper quoted reliable military sources
as saying that the agreement was reached when a high-level Turkish
military delegation visited Egypt two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Turkey's Tusas Aerospace Industries will
provide Egyptian technicians with necessary technical trainings on
F-16 jets.
</P>
<P>
However, it remains unsettled when Turkey will begin to
receive the Egyptian trainees and how many of them will be
involved initially.
</P>
<P>
So far, Turkey has sold 48 F-16 fighter planes to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that this is part of the efforts by Ankara to
further strengthen its military ties with Egypt, the most
influential country in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
They said that the training program might be aimed at
appeasing Cairo which has complained about the quickly expanding
Turkish-Israeli military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Turkey have signed a series of military and defense
accords under which they share airspace and bases for training
purposes.
</P>
<P>
Turkish-Israeli military cooperation has prompted serious
concern among Arab countries who fear it would change the region's
balance of power.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly stated that its military ties with Israel
are of bilateral nature and not directed at any third country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature: Chinese Views of United States (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, many Chinese express disgust with the fact that some
U.S. politicians have attempted to interfere in China's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Ma Hua, a middle school teacher in Beijing's Huairou County,
described various figures on Capitol Hill as extremely
"overbearing".
</P>
<P>
Surveys published by "China Youth Daily" in 1995 and 1996
indicated that some 90 percent of the young respondents believed
that the United States maintained an "unfriendly" attitude towards
China on issues such as Taiwan and human rights.
</P>
<P>
He Zuoxiu, a physicist who participated in China's nuclear bomb
development program in the 1960s, said that President Clinton's
readjusted China policy which advocates the establishment of a
Sino-U.S. strategic partnership has helped change the views of
Chinese towards the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. side should exhibit greater initiative and take more
steps to further Sino-U.S. relations," said He.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xiuying, a worker in a state-owned factory in southwest
China's Chongqing Municipality, said Americans know little about
China and noted that "President Clinton should have visited the
country much earlier".
</P>
<P>
President Clinton will arrive in China on June 25, following a
10 hour flight across the Pacific aboard "Air Force One". By way
of comparison, the U.S. merchant ship "China Queen" spent six
months covering the same distance before arriving in the south
China city of Guangzhou on August 28, 1784, which marked the debut
of Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an, the beginning of the ancient Silk Road which linked the
East and West, will be the first stop in Clinton's China tour.
</P>
<P>
Local residents are busily preparing a grand ceremony to honor
President Clinton, the first U.S. president to visit China in
almost a decade. Xi'an was used for similar ceremonies during
the Tang Dynasty some 1,000 years ago to welcome the most
distinguished foreign guests visiting what was then the strongest
country in the world.  
</P>
