<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Shrinks Further in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' trade deficit
dropped by 62.9 percent to 1.39 billion U.S. dollars from the
year-ago level in the first four months this year, the National
Statistics Office said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The office said in a press release that as of April, the
country's revenue from exports increased by 19.9 percent to 9.1
billion dollars while expenditure for imports shrank by 7.5
percent to 10.5 billion dollars, both on a year-on-year base.
</P>
<P>
For April alone, the total trade contracted by 5.7 percent to
4.74 billion dollars from 5.03 billion dollars last year, the new
release said.
</P>
<P>
Aggregate earnings from exports amounted to 2.28 billion
dollars, up by 9.8 percent while total payment for imports reached
2.46 billion dollars, 16.5 percent lower than the year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
Electronics and components, telecommunication equipment and
electrical machinery, capital goods, raw materials and
intermediate goods were the major imports during the period under
review.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan, Korea and Singapore are major
importers of Philippine products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
