<HEADLINE> British Media Attack Hooligans in Marseille Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Celebration of England's opening
victory in the World Cup finals was overshadowed on Britain's
front pages Tuesday as the media attacked the soccer hooligans.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair on Monday condemned the
violence, which began on Saturday night but has gradually
escalated to rioting before and during Monday's England-Tunisia
match in Marseille.
</P>
<P>
Over 50 people were injured. Police detained nearly 80
Englishman, Tunisians and Frenchmen, and two of the Englishmen
were sentenced to three months in prison.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian on Tuesday quoted the commander of Britain's
police operations at the World Cup as saying authorities expect
more trouble as the soccer tournament progresses and that known
hooligans are either already in France or on their way to
orchestrate more violence.
</P>
<P>
The Times said that city authorities in Marseille, where
England defeated Tunisia 2-0 on Monday, were demanding
compensation from the British government for the damage caused by
English hooligans and that the city's deputy mayor has called for
England to be expelled from the tournament.
</P>
<P>
The Independent newspaper said in an editorial: "The only way
to stop the thugs - and the only appropriate way of saying sorry
to the people of Marseille - is for the team to pack its bags and
catch the first flight home."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also argued that the violence lends weight to
Britain's campaign to host the World Cup in 2006. 
</P>
</TEXT>
