<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rhino Numbers Swell in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The number of rhinos at central
Kenya's Lake Nakuru National Park has increased tremendously
since 1987.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Wildlife Service (KWS) established a rhino sanctuary
at the park in 1987, when 21 rhinos were taken there. Now the
figure hits 71,, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A KWS official was quoted as saying that 27 of the rhinos at
the Lake Nakuru sanctuary are white and the rest black.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, South Africa donated 20 white rhinos to Kenya, ten of
which were taken to the Nakuru sanctuary and the others to Trans
Mara in the southwest.
</P>
<P>
Kenya launched the countrywide Save the Rhino Project in 1984
to stem the spate of poaching which slashed the national herd
from 20,000 in 1970 to only 400 in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi subsequently accorded the
black rhino special protective status.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the rhinos, the Nakuru park, which is famous for
the resident flamingos, has more than 2,000 buffalos and great
numbers of water bucks, gazelles, warthogs, baboons, leopards,
Rothschild giraffes and lions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barclays Bank of Kenya Cuts Base Rate on Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Barclays Bank of Kenya, a leading
bank in the east African state, has reduced its base lending rate
while other commercial banks are expected to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
The Barclays Bank of Kenya's base rate on loans fell from 26
percent to 25 percent with effective from July 1, the bank's
managing director, Gareth George, was quoted Tuesday by meida
here as saying.
</P>
<P>
The move followed last week's budget reading in which the
Kenyan government said it will reduce its borrowing through
short-term Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
George said the one percentage point reduction of the base
rate is significant in the current hard economic times.
</P>
<P>
There may be a further drop in the base rate in the future, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The governor (of the Central Bank of Kenya) was happy with
our decision and we expect that our customers will be excited
too," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
He said the draft budget is encouraging to banks and, if
adhered to, borrowing customers would be encouraged by lower
interest rates to go for loans.
</P>
<P>
"Last week's budget signals that the government's investment
in Treasury bills will reduce, hence will reduce pressure on
interest rates," said George.
</P>
<P>
The banker said his bank is now focusing on specific customers
in its efforts to improve customer relations.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to classifying our corporate customers
and business customers so that we can be more focused," he said.
</P>
<P>
The current high interest rates in Kenya started the upward
trend in July last year after the lapse of the
multi-million-Dollar loan packages by the International Monetary
Fund.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
