<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Official Warns of Global Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior World Bank executive has
warned of global recession if the Asian economic crisis cannot be
properly managed, calling on Japan to stabilize its weak currency.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Michel Severino, World Bank Group vice-president for East
Asia and the Pacific, said the region was unlikely to emerge from
the deep recession until at least the second half of 1999, the
Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
His opinion was backed by Thailand's Deputy Prime Minister
Supachai Panitchpakdi who warned of dire worldwide consequences if
the Japanese currency could not be stabilized.
</P>
<P>
The yen has continued to slide, falling below 145 Monday to the
U.S. dollar, its lowest level since 1990, and has been blamed for
slumps last week in other Asian financial markets.
</P>
<P>
"If the yen dropped with no bottom a second Asian crisis would
take place," Supachai told reporters in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
"That in turn could lead to a world recession."
</P>
<P>
"The whole world should pay more attention to the Japanese
problem."
</P>
<P>
Severino, who with Supachai addressed the Australia Summit
conference on trade and investment, said it was a critical time
for the management of the Asian economic crisis with the outcome
delicately balanced.
</P>
<P>
"We have one crisis behind us and we have entered a period of
deep and probably long-lasting depression (in East Asia),"
Severino said.
</P>
<P>
"Growth rates for the region in 1998 will be in the range of
minus-two to minus-15 percent and the prospects for 1999 are
gloomy as well."
</P>
<P>
About 700 delegates from Asia, Australia and the United States
attended the three-day conference, which began Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
