<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature: Chinese Views of United States (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A well-known Chinese proverb
reads: "The eyes of enemies coming face-to-face blaze with hatred."
</P>
<P>
However, when Han Decai met Harold Fischer in October, 1997,
all former hatred arising from a war over a little over four
decades ago had faded.
</P>
<P>
"Welcome to China and you can invest here," said Han, a
lieutenant general of China's Air Force. Fischer, a real estate
businessman, served as a fighter pilot in the U.S. Air Force
during the Korean War (1950-1953), the only direct wartime
engagement between the Chinese and the U.S. armies.
</P>
<P>
Han downed Fischer's fighter in an air battle on the Korean
Peninsula in 1953. Now, however, their talks shifted to
cooperation, investment and the future.
</P>
<P>
Han, 66, quoted Confucius as saying: "Reproof is useless in
terms of the past, but the future will be provided for."
</P>
<P>
Fischer plans to revisit China at Han's invitation during
U.S. President Bill Clinton's upcoming nine-day state visit.
</P>
<P>
The transition from enemies to business partners and even
friends is an experience not only shared by Han and Fischer, but
also by the United States, the world's most developed country, and
China, the largest developing nation.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted by the Beijing-based Horizon Market
Survey Company indicated that 74 percent of Chinese sampled regard
the U.S. as "either a friend or partner of China". The U.S. is
also the favorite destination for Chinese planning to either
travel or study.
</P>
<P>
However, the combination of distance and time have made the
U.S. "a remote and strange nation" for most Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"Who is Clinton?" asked Liu Wencai, a farmer from Guang'an
County in southwest China's Sichuan Province, the hometown of late
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping. Liu was in Beijing with four other
villagers as tourists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Pressures Yugoslavia With Show of Air Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) held military exercises Monday code named
"Operation Determined Falcon" to pressure Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
A total of 85 warplanes from 13 NATO countries took off on
Monday morning from 15 airbases in five countries including
Italy's Aviano base.
</P>
<P>
They flew over Albania, Macedonia and border areas of
Yugoslavia in a show of force that was intended to end
Yugoslavia's crackdown on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
General Michael C. Short, commander of the U.S. Air Force in
NATO's southern command, said the exercises were to demonstrate
NATO's will to make peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
NATO is demonstrating its ability to move very quickly and
project power, he added.
</P>
<P>
NATO Chief Javier Solana said on Monday the maneuver was very
successful and had achieved its objectives.
</P>
<P>
The allies fear the growing violence in Serbia's Kosovo
province, which is part of Yugoslavia, will spill over into
neighboring Albania and Macedonia, where ethnic Albanians also
live.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people have died since Violence erupted in the
province where more than 90 percent of the population is composed
of ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
