<HEADLINE> News Feature: Chinese Views of United States (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, increasing contacts and media coverage are helping
Chinese to learn more about the far distant country on the other
side of the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese agree that expanding contacts between the two
countries since the early 1980s have helped them learn more about
the U.S. and their memories of the landmark 1972 handshake between
late Chairman Mao Zedong and former U.S. President Richard Nixon
remain fresh in their minds.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the Ministry of Education, a total
of 163,100 Chinese scholars and students visited the U.S. between
1978-1997, accounting for 56 percent of the country's total number
of those studying abroad.
</P>
<P>
"My dream is to earn a doctorate degree in the United States,"
said Zhou Yan, a Beijing middle school student. Just as many of
her classmates, Zhou admires Michael Jordan, enjoyed the Hollywood
blockbuster film "Titanic" and regularly visits local MacDonald's
retaurants.
</P>
<P>
Winning over young consumers like Zhou Yan has to the great
success MacDonald's enjoys in China. The American fast-food giant
has opened 48 restaurants in Beijing alone, including one in
downtown Beijing near Tian'anmen Square.
</P>
<P>
Apart from a MacDonald's Big Mac, most Chinese who will quite
likely have no opportunity to travel abroad are enjoying the
"American Experience" offered by Coca Cola. Most schools offer
English courses which quite often refer to Boeing aircraft, Nike
sneakers and Monsanto cotton seeds.
</P>
<P>
"Americans have established joint ventures in our county, and
they seem concerned about our grain production," said Liu, the
previously mentioned farmer who spoke to Xinhua while sightseeing
in Tian'anmen Square.
</P>
<P>
Lu Qun, an employee of Beijing Jeep Corporation Ltd.,
said that Sino-U.S. economic ties should be enhanced.
</P>
</TEXT>
