<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Economic Foundations Strongest in 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Australia's macro-economic
foundations were the strongest they had been for 25 years,
Australian Prime Minister John Howard said Tuesday in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the Australia Summit, an international meeting
on the financial crisis in Asia, the prime minister talked about
the economic achievements made by his government since it took
power two years ago: low inflation and interest rates, high
economic growth, lower debt and a projected budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
"From being a persistent high inflation economy, Australia now
has an inflation record virtually second to none (1.5 percent) and
the lowest interest rates since 1970s," he told 700 delegates from
Asia and the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
Small business interest rates were now at 7.7 percent and home
loan rates at 6.7 percent, compared with 17.25 percent and 15.5
percent in 1986, respectively, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar devalued by about 20 percent against the
U.S. dollar during the past year under pressure from the Asian
financial crisis, reaching record lows not seen since 1986.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed the differences between economic
fundamentals in 1986 and now.
</P>
<P>
In 1985-1986 fiscal year the budget was in deficit by 4.8
billion Australian dollars, representing 2 percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP), and the nation's budget in 1998-1999
fiscal year would be in surplus by 2.7 billion Australian dollars
(1.6 billion U.S. dollars), or 0.5 percent of GDP, the prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"The underlying inflation was 9.6 percent in the year to
September 1986, underlying inflation is now at 1.5 percent".
</P>
<P>
He also said Australia's debt servicing ratio was cut from 15.3
percent of GDP in 1986 to current 10.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Australia's net debt on current projections would be reduced
from around 20 percent in 1995-1996 fiscal year to 1.5 percent by
2001-2002, a level not seen in the nation for 20 years, Howard
said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian economy grew by 4.9 percent in the year to
March, 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the problems in Asia, our budget still forecasts 3
percent growth in 1998-1999, a strong performance by international
standards."
</P>
<P>
"The OECD (Organization for Economic Co-operation and
Development) predicts that over the two years 1998 and 1999
Australia will grow faster than any of the G7 countries and the
OECD average."
</P>
<P>
"Australia is being affected by the problems in (Asian)
regional economies. But we are in far better shape to weather this
crisis than would have been the case had not put our house in
order", referring to the massive cuts made by his government in
budget deficits during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that the economic downturn in Asia was a matter
for concern given that 57 percent of Australia's merchandise
exports went to East Asia in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
