<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Should Grant China Permanent MFN, Says Daley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States should grant
China a permanent Most-Favored-Nation trade status, a normal trade
relations arrangement between countries in the world, U.S.
Commerce Secretary William Daley said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are very much in favor of getting rid of this year-by-year
sort of review," Daley said at a forum when referring to the
current debate in Congress on China's MFN status.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the TransAmerica Public Policy Forum on China, Daley
said the annual debate "is not helpful to strengthening relations"
between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
At the forum, Daley and other speakers including Republican
Senator Dick Lugar, expressed their confidence that both the
Senate and House of Congress will approve the decision by
President Bill Clinton to grant China MFN status.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who will pay a historical visit to China on June 25,
made the decision early this month to extend China's MFN status
for another year. Congress have a right to debate and vote on the
decision within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Some lawmakers, accusing the administration of transferring
high-technologies to China, and China of human rights violations,
oppose the decision.
</P>
<P>
"But... it's the same, normal treatment we grant virtually all
our trading partners. It's the same policy that has enjoyed the
support of four presidents for every single one of the last 17
years," Daley said.
</P>
<P>
He cited the basic economic reasons: China is the fifth largest
trading partner; its transition to market economy is unleashing
billions of dollars in consumer demand; already about 170,000
American jobs depend on exports to China; China will be the
largest economy by 2030.
</P>
<P>
Noting that to expand exports to China is in the security
interests of the United States, Daley supports selling high-tech
products to China.
</P>
<P>
"It's just not the case anymore that strict American export
regulation alone will keep technology out of the hands of people
who want it," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the U.S.-China relationship is "the most
challenging, complex, and important bilateral relationship in the
world," Daley said, "A policy of engagement between the two is the
only option in the modern world. A policy of estrangement between
the two is unthinkable."
</P>
<P>
Daley's remarks were echoed by Bill Richardson, U.S. Ambassador
to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador told the forum that China, as one permanent
member of the U.N. Security Council, has played and is playing its
leadership role "very effectively and constructively" and the
United States needs its cooperation on a broad range of issues.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States have had good cooperation on a
number of issues ranging from the security in South Asia to
lessening the impact of the financial crisis in South East Asia,
said the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about China's participation of the
G-8, which groups Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan,
the United States and Russia, Richardson said the issue is a "fact
of life" and "something should be considered."
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that China and the United States expand their
cooperation and exchange in culture, education and even sports.
</P>
<P>
The one-day forum was sponsored by the TransAmerica life
Companies, a group which comprises several insurance companys.
Guest speakers also include Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing.
</P>
<P>
The discussion is one of a series of warm-up events just prior
to Clinton's trip, the first by a U.S. president in a decade. It's
a reciprocal visit to the one paid by Chinese President Jiang
Zemin to the United States last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Meat, Fish Sector Expands by 6.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's meat and fish sector
increased by 6.4 percent in its output value in 1997-98 fiscal
year ended March, according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The rise was due to increases in the production of livestock
and fishery, said a report on the country's financial, economic
and social conditions issued by the Ministry of National Planning
and Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
The production of meat increased to 283,294 tons from 268,135
tons, fresh water fish to 239,773 tons from 229,178 tons, marine
fish to 644,502 tons from 602,937 tons, and prawn to 31,459 tons
from 29,340 tons.
</P>
<P>
Total production of fish and prawn increased by 6.3 percent and
7.2 percent respectively over the previous year, the report said,
adding that per capita fish consumption was 17 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The meat and fish sector is the third largest contributor
towards the gross domestic product (GDP) after agriculture and
manufacturing, sharing 7.3 percent of the GDP in the 1997-98
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings of the sector in the fiscal year with fish and
prawn as its major export items reached 167 million U.S. dollars,
surpassing the target of 145 million dollars, another official
report said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, with a long coastline of 2,832 kilometers and
extensive river systems, is rich in both marine and fresh water
fishery resources.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Myanmar has formed more than five joint ventures in
the production of fish and prawn and cultured pearl with companies
from Bangladesh, China, Germany, Japan and Thailand and the
finished products are exported to Australia, China, Japan,
Malaysia, Singapore, the United States, European Market and Middle
East countries.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the meat and fish sector reached about
270 million dollars in 17 related projects at the end of February
this year, according to official statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
