<HEADLINE> British Entrepreneurs to Build Container Port in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Some British entrepreneurs have
formed a consortium to build a private container port in
Bangladesh, according to the latest issue of Economic Times weekly
reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed container port will be built at Patenga Point on
the Bay of Bengal, 80 kilometers southeast of the port city of
Chittagong.
</P>
<P>
The British Department of Trade and Industry (BDTI) was
actively supporting the 290 million U.S. dollar project, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The British government was backing the initiators to implement
the project as it thought Bangladesh had bright prospect for
investment from British-based companies, BDTI's export promoter
David J. Burton was quoted in Dhaka as saying recently.
</P>
<P>
The British export promoter hoped that the container port would
be operative by the year 2002, saying that he was expecting
cooperation from the International Finance Corporation and the
World Bank to implement the project.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are two sea ports -- Chittagong and Mongla,
which can not meet an ever increasing demand for container
handling due to shortage of modern facilities and limited storage
areas. 
