<HEADLINE> THAI Plans for All-Thai Pilot Fleet in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Thai Airways International (THAI),
the national flag carrier, is planning to usher in the year 2000
with only local pilots flying its modern fleet of aircraft, the
Nation said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Captain Chamlong Poompuang, deputy vice president of THAI's
flight operations, said the company is on course for phasing out
the last 11 expatriate pilots in stages over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
He added that it will be the first time in the airline's
history that all its pilots would be Thai. The carrier now has 836
pilots.
</P>
<P>
The company said converting to an all-Thai pilot fleet would
save the airline millions of dollars in annual expenses.
</P>
<P>
The airline is also planning to reduce its types of aircraft in
its fleet from the present nine types to six over the next year,
saving further costs in training. 
