<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capital Flow Remains Tight in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Quoting figures released by the central bank Monday, the
newspaper said the country's foreign reserves stood at 27.5
billion U.S. dollars as of May 29, a drop of 400 million dollars
from May 15, despite continued surpluses in the current account.
</P>
<P>
The decline was attributed to the central bank's settlement of
500 million dollars in forward swap obligations, 300 million with
onshore counterparts and the remainder offshore.
</P>
<P>
Total net forward obligations as of May 29 were 13.4 billion
dollars, among which 11.6 billion with onshore institutions and
the remainder with offshore counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement with the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
the central bank must reduce its forward obligations to 9 billion
dollars by the end of the year, with no offshore obligations
remaining.
</P>
<P>
Foreign reserves also declined due to limited dollar sales by
local commercial banks, the newspaper quoted a central bank
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The baht depreciation and the foreign reserves fall implied
that capital flow over the last two weeks of May were not
favorable, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank increased net lending to financial
institutions by 35.1 billion baht (816 million dollars) to 88.5
billion baht (2.06 billion dollars) in the last two weeks of May.
</P>
<P>
The increase stemmed from mounting demand for funds by
corporations for tax payments, as well as demand by local
institutions to meet liquidity reserve requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Industrial Output Grows In First Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia's industrial
production in the first five months this year rose by 12.2 percent
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Mirjana Rankovic, director of the Statistical Bureau, told
reporters Monday that the industrial output in the Serbia Republic
increased by 13.5 percent while that of the Montenegro Republic
had a 3.6 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
The federation's export during this period under review
totalled 968 million U.S. dollars, a 10.8 percent growth compared
with same period last year, while its import was 1.979 billion
dollars, a rise of 4.8 percent, she said.
</P>
<P>
Wheat output is expected to increase by 3 million tons this
year, the second bump harvest in a row, according to Milan
Prostran, secretary of the Agricultural Committee of the Yugoslav
Economic Federation.
</P>
<P>
Apart from meeting domestic needs, more than 500,000 tons of
wheat are to be exported, Prostran said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
