<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Confident About Asia's Prospects: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard said Tuesday his government was confident about Asia's
prospects, saying it would emerge strengthened from the current
downturn.
</P>
<P>
"I genuinely believe our region can learn from the present
crisis and emerge from it equipped for the next century,
economically stronger and politically more stable," the prime
minister said in Melbourne in an address to the Australia Summit,
an international meeting on the financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The speed and durability of Asia's recovery from its economic
crisis would depend on not turning backwards and inwards but
persisting with reforms that make economies more open and
competitive, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Building solid economic foundations is essential, as are
reformed financial markets and increasing transparency and
accountability in government and corporate decision-making,"
Howard said.
</P>
<P>
"The solutions to the region's current problems lie in knowing
how to use the benefits of globalization -- such as open markets
and foreign investment -- to our advantage," he told the meeting,
which began Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Some in our communities are tempted to blame outside
influences for the problems. They see globalization, especially
global capital flows, as the culprit," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But globalization has brought the capital, technology and
markets that have fueled the growth of regional economies," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Trying to close off our economies from the outside world will
cost us jobs and deny our populations the prospects of improved
living standards," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa, Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi and
Singapore's Minister for Trade and Industry Lee Yock Suan are
among the speakers to 700 delegates at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Also participating at the meeting are international economists,
officials from the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and
the Asian Development Bank, high ranking officials from Japan and
Vietnam, and the ambassadors of India, Indonesia and the United
States in Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
