<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia Proposes Solving Land Dispute with Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Croatia proposed Monday to set up a
mixed commission with Yugoslavia for negotiation on the definition
of a land border on the disputed Prevlaka Peninsula between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The draft agreement on a lasting solution to the issue of
Prevlaka was handed over to Yugoslav Ambassador to Croatia Veljko
Knezevic on Monday by Croatia Foreign Minister Mate Granic.
</P>
<P>
Since the disintegration of the former Yugoslavia in 1991, both
Croatia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia have sought the
ownership of the strategic peninsula which had a large naval
base. The pending territorial dispute has been the major irritant
in the normalization of ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian Foreign Ministry said Croatia put forward the
draft in line with the United Nations Security Council Resolution
1147 which called on Croatia and Yugoslavia to resolve the land
dispute through bilateral negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian draft called for the normalization of relations
between the two countries, and quoted principles from the
U.N. Charter and other international documents on the
inviolability of internationally recognized borders, and the
peaceful solution to disputes.
</P>
<P>
The draft also offered full security in the Dubrovnik region of
southern Croatia and the adjacent Yugoslav region of Boka Kotorska
Bay, by means of mutual demilitarization and respect for the
territorial integrity and sovereignty of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A sea border between the two countries would be determined
according to international conventions, and with the assurance of
a passage to Boka Kotorska Bay, it added.
</P>
<P>
Granic noted that the resolution of the Prevlaka issue, an
obligation of the two countries, would contribute to regional
stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
