<HEADLINE> Thai Rice Mills to Offer 10,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The newspaper said the Labor Ministry has been asked to help
find Thai workers to replace the foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, millers are complaining that because of the
government's policy to repatriate foreign workers starting from
May 1, all rice mills in the country would have to cut their
production capacity by more than 50 percent, or to operate only
eight hours a day.
</P>
<P>
If the Labor Ministry fails to find Thai replacements for more
than 10,000 foreigners whose work permits are due to expire in
November, the industry could suffer a loss of up to about 700
million baht (16.28 million U.S. dollars) per day, Thai Rice Mills
Association Chairman Bamrung Kritphakorn said Monday.
</P>
<P>
At a subcommittee meeting on seeking substitutes for foreign
workers, Bamrung said the association and the Employment
Department would organize a rice mill job fair in a northeastern
province on Wednesday and another in central Saraburi province on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand faces mounting pressure of unemployment due to the
economic crisis since last July. The government estimated that
jobless people may reach two million by the end of the year.
</P>
