<HEADLINE> Myanmar Invites Bids for Gems Extraction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar mines authorities is
inviting more bids from the local private sector to mine gems in
northern Kachin state of the country, official The New Light of
Myanmar newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A 7,800-carat ruby, once discovered in the Khappaya area of the
state, is being exhibited at the gems museum here.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Gems Central Supervisory Committee will allow its
nationals and private companies and organizations to extract gems
at plots in the area, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, rich in precious stones such as gems, jade and diamond
along with other mineral resources, needs capital investment and
technical know-how for the exploitation and utilization to
accelerate its economic development.
</P>
<P>
After the promulgation of Myanmar's new Gemstone Law in
September 1995, local entrepreneurs are allowed to produce,
transport and sell finished gemstones and manufactured jewelry at
home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar's gems and jade are well known in the world, the
country holds gems emporiums annually.
</P>
<P>
In addition to allowing local private sector to mine gems in
the country, Myanmar has also set up joint ventures with companies
from Thailand and Malaysia for the activities.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, the output value
of Myanmar's mining sector, which includes gems and jade, rose 1.5
percent in 1997-98 fiscal year ended March and the production of
gems and jade in the fiscal year went to 24.7 million carats and
2.7 kilos respectively.
</P>
<P>
The export of gems amounted to 25 million dollars in the
previous 1996-97, the statistics added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
