<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Expert Calls for End to U.S. Sanctions on China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. senior fellow Nicholas
R. Lardy from the Brookings Institute call on Monday for an end to
U.S. economic sanctions on China.
</P>
<P>
China has played a very important and constructive role in
dealing with the Asian financial crisis and "has contributed
substantial amounts of money, both multilaterally and even
bilaterally," Lardy said at a press briefing with two other
experts on China at the Brookings Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
"More importantly, it has contributed by affirming that it will
maintain the stability of its exchange rate. This is a country
that has not devalued its currency and currently has the fastest
growing economy by a substantial margin in the Asian region,"
Lardy said.
</P>
<P>
"China's contribution to Asia and its recovery doesn't come
simply through maintaining the stability of its exchange rate, but
sustaining the stability of its economy -- indeed, the forward
growth momentum of the economy," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Because of China's rapid economic growth, it absorbs a lot of
imports from the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"So it's really in our interest not just to applaud China's
ability to maintain the stability of its exchange rate, but we
really ought to be doing something or thinking about various ways
in which we can contribute to this kind of accelerated economic
transition that has become apparent since Zhu Rongji became
premier at a meeting earlier this year."
</P>
<P>
He said the Unite States has acknowledged the important role
China is playing by maintaining the stability of its exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
Lardy said the United States should talk about ways in which it
can step up technical assistance in a variety of areas relating to
China's banking reforms, mortgage market, housing privatization,
the development of a social safety net, and a social security
system.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the United States is the only developed
country, the only advanced industrial economy in the world, that
does not have a technical and economic assistance program for
China.
</P>
<P>
Lardy criticized the delay of China's accession to the World
Trade Organization and the difficulty for permanent U.S. Most
Favored Nation (MFN) status.
</P>
<P>
"China already has permanent MFN from every country in the
world except the United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not even clear that we will be able to deliver permanent
MFN, should China become a member. So the gains to China are
fairly modest and the demands that are being placed on China are
quite substantial."
</P>
<P>
What really needs to be done is to recalibrate the U.S.
position with respect to China's accession, particularly in the
area of financial services, he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting the Asian financial crisis, Lardy said, the Chinese are
moving rapidly to try to address some of the problems in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"To try to get them to sign an agreement that would liberalize
their financial services sector overnight is pushing them off the
cliff," he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the trade relationship between the United States and China,
Lardy said, the relationship is highly beneficial to both
countries.
</P>
<P>
The United States now purchases almost a third of China's
exports. Exports from China are obviously a small percentage of
total U.S. exports. But China is now among the top 10 largest
U.S. export markets, and the fastest-growing U.S. export market.
</P>
<P>
"We are benefiting in terms of jobs that are being
created. Almost all of these jobs are in high-wage sectors," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
What the United States is importing from China is primarily
labor-intensive commodities, he said, adding that American
consumers are benefiting from lower-priced footwear, garments, and
toys.
</P>
<P>
"Although there is a deficit in our trade with China, it is
vastly overstated by the U.S. Department of Commerce. But more
importantly, we are not losing a lot of jobs domestically, because
most of what we are importing from China we used to buy from Hong
Kong or Taiwan or in other places," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So I think the bilateral economic relationship benefits both
countries," Lardy said. "It should be promoted."
</P>
<P>
However, Lardy noted that he was disappointed that the
U.S. economic sanctions against China since 1989 were still there.
</P>
<P>
"It looks like we will get through two summits and we will
still have in place the economic sanctions that were imposed on
China in 1989," he said.
</P>
<P>
Every other advanced industrial economy took those sanctions
off on the economic side in 1992, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's disappointing that after two summits the
administration has not figured out a way to get rid of the last
remaining economic sanctions," Lardy concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
