<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Experts Support Better U.S.-China Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. experts said on Monday
that U.S.-China relations have been improved in the past years
which have benefited both countries and should be further improved
by the upcoming U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
"The strategic dimension of the U.S.-China relationship is
important and growing," said Richard N. Haass, director of Foreign
Policy Studies at the Brookings Institution, at a joint press
briefing together with Nicholas R. Lardy, senior fellow at the
Institution and Bates Gill, director and research professor, East
Asia Non-proliferation Project at the Monterey Institute of
International studies.
</P>
<P>
There is the old problem, but there are the new strategic
issues, or issues of greater strategic prominence stemming from
South Asia, where China is clearly a major influence and a major
factor, and the Korean peninsula, where the United States still
has its military presence in the post-Cold War world, Haass said,
"All these and other areas, the strategic dimension of U.S.-China
relations, what we can work out with one another, is obviously of
paramount importance."
</P>
<P>
The uncoming summit between President Clinton and the Chinese
leaders "is to institutionalize even more this relationship
between two countries whose ability to get along, for better or
worse, will obviously have far-reaching implications as we move
into the new century," said Haass.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the leaders of the two countries will
have the chance to stress their cooperation in much larger areas
from economic stability to regional security.
</P>
<P>
At the briefing, Gill said that the trend is very good in terms
of improving U.S.-China relationships and understandings in the
fields of proliferation and the military-to-military relationships.
</P>
<P>
In the upcoming summit, he said, the U.S. Department of Defense
expects to build upon "a relatively consistent policy of moving
forward, step by step, in strengthening the military-to-military
relationship between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
It will focus on opportunities to gain a greater insight or
transparency, through confidence building, into the doctrinal and
strategic understandings of the Chinese, he added.
</P>
<P>
Gill said, it was expected that at the summit, the two
militaries will reach an agreement to take further steps in
building their relationship in terms of cooperating humanitarian
relief.
</P>
<P>
It was also expected that at least a statement will be issued
that the two sides will be moving forward in reaching a memorandum
of understanding for the two militaries to address environmental
issues, Gill said.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, he said, the two sides are close to reaching an
agreement for an exchange of observers, he said. With an
agreement, the two sides will be able to view each other's
exercises.
</P>
<P>
Gill supports a policy of engagement with China and is against
a policy of isolation. He said the meetings between leaders of the
two countries will contribute to a greater dialogue in the United
States and its relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
"One of the greatest problems we face, of course, is that it's
a country we do not understand very well," Gill said. The only way
to change that is "to devote greater resources, a greater amount
of time, greater amount of our efforts to understanding China."
That can only be done through a policy of engagement, added Gill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's National People's Congress Leader Ends Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Vice Chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of the
People's Republic of China Xie Fei left here Tuesday for home
after a three-day official goodwill visit to Brunei.
</P>
<P>
During the visit at the invitation by the Brunei government,
Xie Fei had separate meetings with Brunei's Sultan and Supreme
Head of State Haji Hassanal Bolkiah and Brunei Foreign Minister
Mohammed Bolkiah.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting between Xie and the Sultan, the two sides shared
the view that further strengthening good neighborly friendship
between the two countries conforms to the fundamental interests of
the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Xie Fei said China would continue to adhere to the policy of
good neighborliness and friendship and would actively promote the
mutually beneficial cooperation with neighboring countries
including Brunei.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral cooperation, Xie said that there exist great
potentials for cooperation between China and Brunei and both sides
could learn from each other for common development in many fields.
</P>
<P>
The Brunei Sultan described various policies being pursued by
China as correct and expressed his belief that under the
leadership of Chinese President Jiang Zemin, China will be
successful in achieving its objective of modernization.
</P>
<P>
The Sultan said bilateral relations between Brunei and China
are very good and there exist no obstacles in the development of
cooperation between the two countries, and he pledged that Brunei
will work towards further strengthening the bilateral cooperation
between the two countries especially in the economic and trade
field.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Brunei foreign minister, during his meeting with
Xie, spoke highly of the achievements made in the development of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Xie informed the Brunei foreign minister of China's efforts in
promoting peace and development in the region and stressed that
nations, big or small, are equal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
