<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals in Indonesia May Drop 50 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Indonesia may
drop 50 percent if the current political and social situation
persists, The Jakarta Post Tuesday quoted an official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Many tours, including some for much later this year, have been
canceled because people are still not confident about security
here," the Indonesian Tourism Promotion Board chairman Pontjo
Sutowo said in a written report for the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists dropped by 16.1 percent between January
and April from the same period last year. Riots from May 14 to 17
in the country caused a further drastic slump, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It predicts tourist arrivals in the country may drop 50 percent
from the 5.2 million visitors reported in 1997. Last year,
revenues generated through tourism reached 6.6 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Pontjo said that occupancy rates in Jakarta's four and
five-star hotels sunk to an average of around 10 percent, and many
conferences and conventions had also been canceled.
</P>
<P>
Even in Bali, the country's most popular tourist destination,
occupancy rates did not exceed 30 percent currently.
</P>
<P>
Pontjo said that political instability remained the biggest
worry for tourists considering a visit to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
