<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Chinese City Battles Yellow River Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Puyang, a city in central China's
Henan Province which was long been plagued by flooding, has found
a new way to ensure safety.
</P>
<P>
The city is located in the middle and lower reaches of the
Yellow River, China's second longest following the Yangtze. More
than 300,000 Puyang residents living in the surrounding flood
plain face the dangers of flooding.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers have employed every possible means to survive
flooding, with the most effective method involving the
construction of elevated platforms which provide families with a
safe place during floods.
</P>
<P>
The city government recognized the effectiveness of the method
and in 1996 initiated a project to reinforce the system by
providing each village with a single platform in order to improve
safety and save land.
</P>
<P>
Puyang allocated 50 million yuan for the construction of
platforms by end of April, with the new system providing enhanced
safety for over 230,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Local riverbeds have long been subject to silting, with
flooding in 1996 leaving 126,000 people homeless and some 238,000
local residents in poverty. The flood also resulted in direct
economic losses of over two billion yuan, or more than the total
local GNP for the previous 12 years combined.  
</P>
</TEXT>
