<HEADLINE> NATO Pressures Yugoslavia With Air Power Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 15 (Xinhua) -- NATO conducted a four-hour air
exercise in Albania and Macedonia on Monday; both countries share
borders with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported that 80 U.S. jet
fighters and 12 planes from other NATO countries took part in the
maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
Reports from other agencies said that the maneuvers, dubbed
Operation Determined Falcon, were a demonstration of NATO
muscle-flexing that could be a prelude to armed intervention in
Kosovo, a troubled province of the Yugoslav Republic of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
The planes took off from air bases in countries that included
Italy, Greece, France, Germany, Britain, the Netherlands and from
NATO ships anchored in the Adriatic Sea, Tanjug added.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the air exercise as a complete success, NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana said in London on Monday that NATO
would use force to help end the Kosovo crisis if necessary.
</P>
<P>
On whether air strikes could proceed without U.N. Security
Council approval, Solana said,"We would prefer to act with
security council resolution ... but a relevant legal basis may be
wider."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said in Warsaw that NATO's
display of air power over the Balkans on Monday demonstrated its
resolve to end the fighting in Kosovo and its ability to rapidly
mobilize lethal air power.
</P>
<P>
Cohen hoped that Russian President Boris Yeltsin would succeed
in persuading Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, who was on a
visit to Russia, to end the Serbian military suppression over the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo are seeking independence
from Serbia. Washington has said that it would not support an
independent Kosovo, but insist more autonomy should be given to
the ethnic Albanians, who comprise 90 percent of Kosovo's
population.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the Kosovo crisis as an internal affair of
Yugoslavia, Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister Zoran Lilic said Friday
that if NATO forces intervened militarily, Yugoslav troops would
take all necessary means to resist the enemy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
