<HEADLINE> U.S. World Championship Team May Drop NBA Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States might enter
the world basketball championship without its 12 NBA players,
according to a report reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In response to a threatened player boycott of the world
championship, starting on July 29 in Athens, Greece, U.S.
basketball authorities are likely to drop their NBA players
already chosen.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for submitting 24-man rosters to FIBA was set on
Friday, so a decision must be made within four days.
</P>
<P>
Options include entering the 12-man Goodwill Games team, made
up of college players, or Americans playing overseas.
</P>
<P>
The NBA players decided they would not commit to playing as
long as a lockout seems likely July 1 when the NBA's labor
agreement expires.
</P>
<P>
"I think we'll just have to send another team," said NBA deputy
commissioner Russ Granik, who also serves as president of USA
Basketball."That will be my recommendation."
</P>
<P>
The 12 NBA players chosen for the U.S.team are: Tim Duncan, Tim
Hardway, Vin Baker, Gary Payton, Terrell Brandon, Kevin Garnett,
Tom Gugliotta, Grant Hill, Allan Houston, Christian Laettner, Glen
Rice and Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
The world championship will be held in Athens, Greece, from
July 29 to August 9. This will be the fourth U.S. national team to
use NBA players. Rudy Tomjanovich of the Houston Rockets will
coach the team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
