<HEADLINE> French, Germans Nail War Crimes Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 15 (Xinhua) -- NATO-led Multinational
Stabilization Force (SFOR) Monday arrested Milorad Krnojelac, a
Serbian war criminal suspect.
</P>
<P>
Krnojelac was wanted by the International Criminal Tribunal for
Former Yugoslavia (ICTY).
</P>
<P>
French and German troops in the force conducted the move with
French special troops playing a coordinating role, the Tanjug news
agency quoted the French Defense Ministry's press bulletin as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The suspect, a former warden of a Foca prison in Bosnia and
Herzegovina, was then sent to The Hague, in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The French Defense Ministry called the move an act under the
United Nations 1088 resolution and the Dayton Accord.
</P>
<P>
This was the first case in which French troops in the SFOR have
caught a Yugoslav war criminal suspect in their controlled area.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Ms. Louise Arbur, chief prosecutor of the ICTY,
accused the French section of the SFOR of passiveness in catching
war criminals.
</P>
<P>
In April, a Washington Post release said that during his
service in Bosnia and Herzegovina, a French officer had leaked to
Radovan Karadzic, a leading war criminal suspect wanted by the
ICTY, details of a plan to arrest him. 
</P>
