<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian police have intercepted
the attempted smuggling of three five-year-old children to
neighboring Turkey, the Interior Ministry's press office said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The children were found hidden in a special compartment near
the engine of a bus belonging to the Turkish Avar company
servicing the Sofia-Istanbul route during a routine check of
vehicles by police at a parking lot in Haskovo, southern Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
A woman on the bus claimed to be the mother of one of the
children. She said the four were bound for Edirne, Turkey, where
they were expected by family members.
</P>
<P>
The police said the two bus drivers, identified as Djamal Kuklu
and Djaik Cubukcu, of Istanbul, tried to bribe the officers with
6,000 Deutsche marks (3,300 U.S. dollars) when the hidden children
were found.
</P>
<P>
They later said the money was what they got for promising to
take the children to Edirne.
</P>
<P>
The two drivers have been arrested and an investigation is
underway, police said. 
</P>
