<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Biggest Shipyard Under Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Pudong New Area of Shanghai will
be the home of the biggest shipyard in China by the year of 2001,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The Waigaoqiao Shipyard, which is now under tense construction,
will have an area of 14.5 hectares where buildings with a combined
floor space of 25,859 sq m will be constructed.
</P>
<P>
The project is estimated to cost 4.7 billion yuan, the
newspaper quoted an official responsible for the construction as
saying.
</P>
<P>
China's shipbuilding industry reached 2.2 million tons in
output last year, accounting for five percent of the world's
total.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that ship demand worldwide will hit 37 million
tons by 2005.
</P>
<P>
The official said that large-tonnage ships would have a ready
market since ship owners try to reduce transport costs by shipping
more cargo per boat.
</P>
<P>
"However, China currently has no ability to compete in this
area due to a lack of a large shipyard," said the official.
"Waigaoqiao Shipyard will further improve China's ability to build
large-tonnage vessels."
</P>
<P>
Waigaoqiao Shipyard will be able to produce 11 ships a year,
each with more than 100,000 dead weight tonnages (DWT). The
biggest boats will be 500,000 DWTs.
</P>
<P>
The shipyard will use the world's latest equipment and
computer monitoring system to ensure efficient technology and
production management.
</P>
<P>
Orders have already started to flow in from the United States
and Hong Kong, according to information from Shanghai-based
Jiangnan Shipbuilding Group, the owner of Waigaoqiao Shipyard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
