<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Lays Off 5,000 Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) has
decided to retrench about 5,000 workers in the hope of saving the
airline from total collapse.
</P>
<P>
In a notice published Tuesday in major Manila newspapers, PAL
said it had to lay off 37 percent of its work force in order to
survive, blaming the 11-day strike by some 620 PAL pilots for the
"irreparable damage" done to the already financially troubled
airline.
</P>
<P>
The dismissal came in the wake of a decision by the Department
of Labor and Employment upholding the management's decision to
retire the 620 pilots who have struck since June 5.
</P>
<P>
The pilots struck in discontent with the management's plan that
they must retire after serving in the company for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Before the walkout, PAL had already been groaning allegedly
from ruinous competition and short of funds as the result of the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We have no other recourse but to downsize; the life of the
company is at stake," said a PAL official who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
He added that the latest strike damaged the company's cash
flow, exacerbating an already cash-strapped position and putting a
squeeze on the airline's ability to service its maturing loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
