<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Sets New Goals for Auto Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 16 (Xinhua) -- This capital of south China's
Guangdong Province expects to raise the sales of its automobile
industry to 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars) in three
years, from 1.28 billion yuan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The city, which completed major restructuring of its auto
industry recently, is also pledging to eradicate losses in this
sector within three years.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on the local automobile industry held here today,
Zhang Guangning, Guangzhou's deputy mayor, said that the city will
spare no efforts to develop its auto industry into a new economic
growth focus and a pillar industry.
</P>
<P>
The sector has undergone twists and turns in its 40 years of
development. A major setback was the cooperation with French car
giant Peugeot which incurred two billion yuan of debts for the
Guangzhou Automobile Group, the Chinese partner. As a major step
in the restructuring, Peugeot was replaced by Japan's Honda
Automobile Company.
</P>
<P>
As part of a new development plan, the city will focus on
building four automobile bases.
</P>
<P>
The first will be a sedan-production base, mainly involving
the Guangzhou Honda Car Company.
</P>
<P>
The second will be a bus-production center composed of three
old enterprises now under the Guangzhou Automobile Group, and a
foreign partner, which is still being sought.
</P>
<P>
The third will be a light-duty vehicle base and the fourth, an
auto parts and components base.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will also be made to improve the work of the
Automobile Research and Development Center in the South China
University of Science and Engineering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
