<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Extends Mandate to U.N. Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
adopted a resolution Monday, giving another year of mandate to the
U.N. Mission in Bosnia-Herzegovina (UNMIBH) until June 21, 1999 to
do more work for the stability in the Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
The UNMIBH, with its current mandate expiring on June 21,
comprises a 2,1011 member police unit contributed by 42 countries,
and aims at training and advising the newly established local
police forces.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report to the Security Council, U.N.
Secretary-general Kofi Annan said the last three months have seen
an increase in Bosnia in violent incidents aimed at returning
refugees.
</P>
<P>
The UNMIBH "will do everything in its power to further advance
the restructuring of the local police forces in order to help
create confidence for returning minorities," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"However, it would be overly optimistic to expect a decisive
change before the nationwide elections scheduled for 13
September 1998," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, some 20,000 refugees have
returned to Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
The UNMIBH was established in February 1996 to help parties
concerned with the implementation of peace accords, local elections
and low enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Taking the floor at the council's consultations, Chinese
Permanent Representative to the U.N. Qin Huasun said that China
still believes that the multinational stabilization force in
Bosnia-Herzegovina (SFOR) must not misuse force in implementing
its mandate.
</P>
<P>
The invocation of Chapter VII of the U.N. Charter is not
applicable to the provisions concerning the UNMIBH and the IPTF
(International Police Task Force), he said.
</P>
<P>
In implementing the actions authorized by the council
resolutions, the Stabilization Force (SFOR) must accept the
political guidance of the council and report to it on time on the
implementation of its tasks, he added.
</P>
<P>
He then voted in favor of the draft resolution put forward by
France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Portugal, Russia, Slovenia, Sweden,
Britain and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Plunges to 12-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil futures Monday plunged
to a 12-year low on the New York Mercantile Exchange after a
United Nations official suggested economic sanctions against Iraq
could end soon, indicating increased oil output.
</P>
<P>
Heating oil and unleaded gasoline futures also fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
Crude for July delivery fell 1.03 cents, or 8.2 percent, to
11.56 U.S. dollars a barrel, after earlier hitting a low of 11.42
U.S. dollars a barrel. July heating oil fell 1.42 cents to 36.70
cents a gallon; July unleaded gasoline fell 1.36 cents to 44.94
cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
Crude fell to its lowest level since August 1986 after the head
of a United Nations team searching for Iraqi chemical and
biological weapons said that Iraq could be allowed to return to
the world oil market in about two months.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have tumbled 49 percent since October as supplies
continue to build in the United States and elsewhere because world
oil producers are flooding those markets to compensate for
extremely weak demand from Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980616.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Ghana Sign Aid Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ACCRA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- China and Ghana Monday signed an
agreement on the free economic aid rendered by the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
The accord was inked between visiting Chinese Foreign Minister
Tang Jiaxuan and his Ghanaian counterpart Victor Gbeho after an
exchange of views on bilateral trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also exchanged views on international and
regional issues of common interest, a Chinese foreign ministry
spokesman told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting later, President Jerry Rawlings of Ghana
expressed satisfaction with the development of the relationship
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Rawlings, African countries have been
increasingly aware that the continent should not only improve but
also enhance cooperation with China in various aspects.
</P>
<P>
In the same vein, Ghana is to devote itself to expanding and
deepening its relations with China, said Rawlings, who also
expressed thanks to China for its disinterested assistance to
Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Responding, Minister Tang said, China and Ghana boast their
friendly relations and that the friendship, established and
cultivated by leaders of the old generation of the two countries,
is deeply rooted.
</P>
<P>
As developing countries, he said, both countries are facing
the same task of safeguarding national stability, developing
economy and maintaining friendly relations with neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are also working together to the
establishment of a new, just and fair international political and
economic order, said Tang, who arrived here Sunday for a two-day
visit.
</P>
<P>
According to Tang, China and Ghana have attained encouraging
achievements in their trade and economic cooperation on the basis
of equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Several projects built in Ghana by the Chinese side have
contributed to the social and economic development of the west
African country.
</P>
<P>
As the two economies are highly complementary, there is great
potential for further cooperation in the future, said Tang, who
became China's foreign minister three months ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the two sides have agreed to work
together to explore new ways and methods to step up trade and
economic cooperation on the basis of mutual benefit in order to
make the cooperation an example of South-South cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to increase visits by senior leaders
of both countries to promote the further development of bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministries of the two countries will hold
consultations in various forms to promote understanding and
cooperation between the two sides in bilateral and multilateral
fields.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday morning, Tang also met with Ghana's Deputy
Speaker Ken Dzirasah.
</P>
<P>
Ghana is the third stop of Tang's five-nation west African
tour. The Chinese minister already visited Guinea and Cote
d'Ivoire and is to leave Tuesday for Togo and Benin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
