<HEADLINE> Kosovo, High Concern for NATO: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The developments in Kosovo are a
matter of high concern for NATO, and the North Atlantic Alliance
seeks solutions to the conflict and militates in favor of a
peaceful way of dialogue, NATO Deputy Secretary General
Klaus-Peter Klaiber said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Alliance pays much attention to this problem
as it is more than desirable to avoid what happened in Bosnia not
very long ago, said Klaiber in his meeting with Romanian Prime
Minister Radu Vasile. NATO is set to prevent any possible way to
extend in the region the conflict in Kosovo, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Klaiber welcomed Romania's part in the regional cooperation and
described it as "a significant contribution to the area
stability." "Romania is NATO's important political and strategic
partner that makes an active contribution to the joint efforts for
keeping peace and stability in Europe," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Klaiber also held talks with Romanian Foreign
Minister Andrei Plesu.
</P>
<P>
As it was reported, Plesu said last week that Romania could not
fail to honor the commitments it made at meetings with the Contact
Group, if NATO declared war to Yugoslavia. "But the Romanians hope
from the bottom of their heart that military solutions would be
shunned and political dialogue would have the last word," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
