<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Continues Moving Higher Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar Monday charged
toward yet another eight-year high against the yen as slumping
Japanese and other Asian markets forced more traders to surrender
their yen stock.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose to 146.15 yen at the closing in New York, up
from 144.72 yen Friday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was changing hands at 1.8105 marks, up from 1.8056
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The yen has been weakening since early this year, and it is now
hovering at its third eight-year low in a week.
</P>
<P>
Traders have fled the yen on continuing bad news about the
Japanese economy. Government figures released Friday showed that
Japan is in the midst of its deepest recession in more than 50
years.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the yen's early fall Monday caused most other Asian
markets to decline as well. Key stock indexes in both Hong Kong and
Bangkok, Thailand, tumbled nearly 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
1.5065 Swiss francs, up from 1.4984; 6.0725 French francs, up from
6.0545; 1,786.98 Italian lire, up from 1,779.00; and 1.4728
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4693.
</P>
<P>
The British pound rose to 1.6353 U.S. dollars, up from 1.6324
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
