<HEADLINE> Some 30 European Countries to Sign Environment Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- About 30 European countries are
expected to sign a new "environmental rights" treaty currently
under negotiation in Geneva by the 55 members of the U.N. Economic
Commission for Europe (ECE), but two of its members from North
America might not sign it.
</P>
<P>
The Convention on Access to Information, Public Participation
in Decision-making and Access to Justice in Environmental Matters
is meant to ensure that the public has a say in decisions relating
to water, soil and air pollution as well as biological diversity
issues such as genetically modified organisms.
</P>
<P>
The convention is a "radical step" not only for eastern
European countries but also some of their Western counterparts,
Kaj Baerlund, director of the ECE Environment and Human
Settlements Division, said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the convention would "change legislation and management
cultures" across Europe "to provide a broad range of easily
accessible environmental information."
</P>
<P>
"The final decisions, of course, will still be made by
politicians.... But there should be less conflict after the
decision-making," said Baerlund, a former Finnish environment
minister.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, diplomats and U.N. sources say Canada and the United
States have not taken part in the latest talks ahead of the
three-day ministerial signing conference opening on June 23 in
Aarhus, Denmark, an indication that they do not intend to sign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
