<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Israel Sends Wrong Signal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Monday
that Israel's demolition of Arab houses in East Jerusalem had sent
"the wrong signal" and called on the Jewish state to refrain from
such "provocative acts."
</P>
<P>
"At the time when we are trying to bring the parties (Israelis
and Palestinians) together, these house demolitions send the wrong
signal," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, Israeli authorities demolished three
Palestinian homes that they said were built without permits in
Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"At this delicate moment in the talks, where we are still
hopeful that we can reestablish the peace process... we renew our
call on both sides to refrain from provocative acts, which only
make the task of reaching agreement more difficult," he added.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said there had been some progress made in recent weeks in
its efforts to restart stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace talks,
although differences still remained between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"There has been progress in recent weeks or we wouldn't be
still at this," Rubin said. "But in the Middle East peace process,
an inch is as good as a mile when it comes to an agreement. And we
have not reached an agreement."
</P>
<P>
The United States is seeking an Israeli troop withdrawal from a
further 13 percent of the West Bank, while the Palestinian
Authority strengthens its measures for security. After that the
United States said the two parties would enter into final status
talks. But the U.S. proposal was rejected by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Rubin reaffirmed previous U.S. statement that if agreement
looked impossible, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright would
call a halt to the current mediation effort. But he indicated that
there was still something to hope for.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue working with the parties as long as they are
constructive and as long as we believe there is a possibility to
reach an agreement," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
