<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin Discuss Kosovo Over Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) - U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin discussed ways Monday to end
ethnic violence in Kosovo without force by phone, the White House
said.
</P>
<P>
"They explored in detail the prospects for getting an outcome
here that would not require getting an `all necessary means
resolution,' but I think it's very clear and certainly the Russian
government knows that we intend to proceed with that type of a
resolution if necessary," White House spokesman Mike McCurry told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Washington would pursue a U.N. resolution authorizing "all
necessary means" if needed, stressed McCurry following the
40-minute talks between the two presidents.
</P>
<P>
"The two presidents were in agreement that it's important to
work together to find the right diplomatic approaches that can
convince (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic and his regime to
do the right thing," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is expected to meet Milosevic Tuesday in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies want Moscow to persuade Milosevic to
agree to a series of demands, including an end to all action by
Serbian security forces against civilians and the withdrawal of
repressive units from the province.
</P>
<P>
Russia differs with its Western partners in the Contact Group
on former Yugoslavia on how the crisis should be resolved and
opposes the use of outside force.
</P>
<P>
"President Yeltsin indicated that he was going to do everything
he could to convince Mr. Milosevic of the precariousness of
Serbia's position," McCurry added.
</P>
<P>
"We believe and we understand the Russian president intends to
deliver a tough message to Milosevic, and we hope that the Serbian
leader is finally wise enough to take advantage of this
opportunity," State Department spokesman James Rubin told another
a briefing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
